record_data.record_plain_text: Great Valley Solar 1, LLC Market-Based Rate Tariff 1. Availability: Great Valley Solar 1, LLC ("Seller") makes electric energy, capacity and ancillary services available under this Tariff for wholesale sales to purchasers with whom Seller has contracted. Seller makes certain ancillary services available under this Tariff for wholesale sales to purchasers with whom Seller has contracted, subject to the limitations below. Specifically, Seller may sell the ancillary services specified below into the following markets: California: Seller offers regulation service, spinning reserve service, and non-spinning reserve service to the California Independent System Operator Corporation ("CAISO") and to others that are self-supplying ancillary services to the CAISO. Third Party Provider: Seller offers Regulation Service, Reactive Supply and Voltage Control Service, Energy and Generator Imbalance Service, Operating Reserve-Spinning, Operating Reserve-Supplemental, and Primary Frequency Response Service. Sales will not include the following: (1) sales to an RTO or an ISO, i.e., where that entity has no ability to self-supply ancillary services but instead depends on third parties; and (2) sales to a traditional, franchised public utility affiliated with the third-party supplier, or sales where the underlying transmission service is on the system of the public utility affiliated with the third-party supplier. Sales of Operating Reserve-Spinning and Operating Reserve-Supplemental will not include sales to a public utility that is purchasing ancillary services to satisfy its own open access transmission tariff requirements to offer ancillary services to its own customers, except where the Commission has granted authorization. Sales of Regulation Service and Reactive Supply and Voltage Control Service will not include sales to a public utility that is purchasing ancillary services to satisfy its own open access transmission tariff requirements to offer ancillary services to its own customers, except at rates not to exceed the buying public utility transmission provider's OATT rate for the same service or where the Commission has granted authorization. 2. Applicability: This schedule is applicable to all sales of energy, capacity, or ancillary services by Seller not otherwise subject to a particular rate schedule or contract of Seller. 3. Rates: All sales hereunder shall be made at rates established by agreement between the purchaser and Seller. 4. Other Terms and Conditions: All other terms and conditions of sale shall be established by agreement between the purchaser and Seller. 5. Compliance with Commission Regulations: Seller shall comply with the provisions of 18 C.F.R. Part 35, Subpart H, as applicable, and with any conditions the Commission imposes in its orders concerning Seller's market-based rate authority, including orders in which the Commission authorizes Seller to engage in affiliate sales under this Tariff or otherwise restricts or limits the Seller's market-based rate authority. Failure to comply with the applicable provisions of 18 C.F.R. Part 35, Subpart H, and with any orders of the Commission concerning Seller's market-based rate authority, will constitute a violation of this Tariff. 6. Limitations and Exemptions Regarding Market-Based Rate Authority: The Commission granted Seller in Great Valley Solar 1, LLC, Docket No. ER17-____-000 et al. (2017) the following waivers and blanket authorization: (i) waiver of Parts 41, 101 (with the exception that waiver of the provisions of Part 101 that apply to hydropower licensees is not granted with respect to licensed hydropower projects), and 141 of the Commission's regulations, except for Sections 141.14 and 141.15; (ii) waiver of Subparts B and C of Part 35 of the Commission's regulations, except for Section 35.12(a), 35.13(b), 35.15 and 35.16; and (iii) blanket approval as to Section 204 of the FPA and Part 34 of the Commission's regulations for all future issuances of securities and debt and assumptions of liabilities. 7. Seller Category: Seller is a Category 2 Seller, as defined in 18 C.F.R. 35.36(a), in the Southwest Region. Seller is a Category 1 Seller, as defined in 18 C.F.R. 35.36(a), in the Northeast, Southeast, Central, Northwest, and Southwest Power Pool Regions. 8. Effective Date: This Tariff is effective on such date set by the Commission.

Rojo, Amarillo, Azul, and Verde are collectively referred to herein as the "Project Companies" and individually as a "Project Company". The Project Companies, together with the Manager, are collectively referred to herein as the "Parties" and individually as a "Party". The terms "Project Company" and "Party" shall include the permitted successors and permitted assignees of such Person. Certain capitalized terms used in this Agreement are given defined meanings in Appendix A attached hereto. RECITALS A. Rojo holds or anticipates holding certain real property option, leasehold, right-of-way and/or fee interests in all or a portion of that certain land located in Fresno County, California (the "Rojo Property"), on which it intends to develop a 100 MWAC solar energy generation project and certain related interconnection facilities (the "Rojo Project"). The Rojo Property is described on the attached Exhibit A-1. B. Amarillo holds or anticipates holding certain real property option, leasehold, right-of-way and/or fee interests in all or a portion of that certain land located in Fresno County, California (the "Amarillo Property"), on which it intends to develop a 20 MWAC solar energy generation project and certain related interconnection facilities (the "Amarillo Project"). The Amarillo Property is described on the attached Exhibit A-2. C. Azul holds or anticipates holding certain real property option, leasehold, right-of-way and/or fee interests in all or a portion of that certain land located in Fresno County, California (the "Azul Property"), on which it intends to develop a 20 MWAC solar energy generation project and certain related interconnection facilities (the "Azul Project"). The Azul Property is described on the attached Exhibit A-3. D. Verde holds or anticipates holding certain real property option, leasehold, right-of-way and/or fee interests in all or a portion of that certain land located in Fresno County, California (the "Verde Property"), on which it intends to develop a 60 MWAC solar energy generation project and certain related interconnection facilities (the "Verde Project"). The Verde Property is described on the attached Exhibit A-4. E. The Project Companies have entered into that certain Large Generator Interconnection Agreement among Rojo, Verde, Amarillo, Azul, Pacific Gas and Electric Company ("PG&E"), and the California Independent System Operator Corporation ("CAISO"), dated as of November 2, 2016 (as so amended, the "Interconnection Agreement"), which relates to the interconnection of the Projects to the CAISO controlled transmission system with a Point of Interconnection at PG&E's 230 kV Tranquillity Switching Station. The Project Companies have entered into that certain LGIA Co-Tenancy Agreement dated as of March 1, 2017 (the "Co-Tenancy Agreement," with Rojo acting as "Manager" thereunder), relating to the sharing of rights and responsibilities under the Interconnection Agreement. E. The Rojo Project, the Amarillo Project, the Azul Project, and the Verde Project are individually referred to herein as a "Project," and collectively as the "Projects." The Rojo Property, the Amarillo Property, the Azul Property, and the Verde Property, are individually referred to herein as a "Property," and collectively as the "Properties." F. The Project Companies hold or anticipate holding, as tenants in common, undivided interests in certain real property options, franchise, leasehold, easement and co-tenancy rights, rights-of-way, encroachment rights, crossing rights, rights under non-disturbance agreements, rights under waivers, rights under consents and/or fee interests described in Exhibit B-1 (the "Shared Premises Property Rights") relating to the property described in Exhibit B-2 (such premises subject to the Shared Premises Property Rights, the "Shared Premises"). G. The Project Companies individually hold or anticipate holding the easement rights described in Exhibit B-3 relating to the property described in Exhibit B-4 (the "Commonly Held Easements") and intend to use and to share the rights and obligations with respect to the Commonly Held Easements as if they were Shared Premises Property Rights and Shared Premises hereunder. H. The Project Companies wish to share the use and cost of certain electrical transmission, communications and other structures and facilities and associated real property rights, and to engage Manager to construct, operate, maintain, repair and manage the foregoing, all in accordance with and subject to the terms and conditions of this Agreement. NOW, THEREFORE, in consideration of the mutual promises contained herein, and for other good and valuable consideration, the receipt and sufficiency of which are hereby acknowledged by the Parties, the Parties agree as follows: ARTICLE 1 DEFINITIONS AND INTERPRETATIONS 1.1 Definitions. As used in this Agreement, including the Recitals, and except as required by grammatical usage and apart from proper nouns, each capitalized term has the meaning given to it in this Agreement and in the Schedule of Definitions attached as Appendix A. 1.2 Interpretation. In this Agreement, unless a clear, contrary intention appears: (a) the singular includes the plural and vice versa; (b) reference to any Person includes such Person's successors and assigns but, in the case of a Project Company, only if such assigns are permitted by this Agreement, and reference to a Person in a particular capacity excludes such Person in any other capacity; (c) reference to any gender includes each other gender; (d) reference to any agreement (including this Agreement), document or instrument means such agreement, document or instrument as amended or modified and in effect from time to time in accordance with the terms thereof and, if applicable, the terms of this Agreement; (e) reference to any Governmental Requirement means such Governmental Requirement as amended, modified, codified, or reenacted, in whole or in part, and in effect from time to time, including, if applicable, rules and regulations promulgated thereunder; (f) reference to any Section means such Section of this Agreement, and references in any Section or definition to any clause means such clause of such Section or definition; (g) "hereunder," "hereof," "hereto" and words of similar import shall be deemed references to this Agreement as a whole and not to any particular Section or other provision of this Agreement; (h) "including" means including without limiting the generality of any description such term; and (i) relative to the determination of any period of time, "from" means "from and including", "to" means "to but excluding" and "through" means "through and including". ARTICLE 2 SHARED PREMISES 2.1 Declaration of Intention. The Project Companies hereby declare that their relationship in and to the Shared Premises Property Rights (not including the Commonly Held Easements) and the Shared Facilities is and will be that of tenants in common, and that each Project Company will have an undivided interest in the Shared Premises and the Shared Facilities on and subject to the terms, conditions, limitations and requirements set forth in this Agreement. The arrangements and ownership structure contemplated by this Agreement are not being made with the intention or expectation of producing revenue or making or sharing in any profits from the ownership or operation of the Shared Premises or the Shared Facilities, but are instead intended as a form of legal ownership whereby the Project Companies can accomplish their respective objectives of independently owning and operating their respective undivided interests in, and sharing the use of, the Shared Premises and the Shared Facilities in connection with their respective Projects and businesses and to enable the Project Companies to perform and discharge certain of their obligations under the Interconnection Agreement, the Co-Tenancy Agreement, and their respective Power Purchase Agreements. Shared Premises Property Rights and Shared Premises as used above in this Section 2.1 shall not be interpreted as including the Commonly Held Easements. The Project Companies acknowledge that they each separately own an undivided interest in the Commonly Held Easements (as applicable) and that although the Commonly Held Easements are not part of the Shared Premises Property Rights or Shared Premises, the Commonly Held Easements shall be treated as Shared Premises Property Rights and Shared Premises in accordance with Section 2.2(c). 2.2 Shared Premises Property Rights. (a) The Shared Premises Property Rights (not including the Commonly Held Easements) as of the Agreement Date, including, if applicable, any such rights that are expected to be obtained after the Agreement Date, are described on Exhibit B-1 in the locations described and depicted on Exhibit B-2. The Shared Premises Property Rights allow or will allow for the development, design, construction, Operation and Maintenance of the Shared Facilities. (b) Each Project Company shall own and hold an interest in the Shared Premises Property Rights (not including the Commonly Held Easements), jointly, as tenants-in-common, for the joint use of the Shared Facilities as provided herein. Without limiting the generality of the foregoing, the foregoing individual interest shall include (i) the joint exercise of the Shared Premises Property Rights on, over, under, across and through the Shared Premises, and (ii) the joint use of those certain Shared Facilities located on or under the Shared Premises (whether now existing or hereafter constructed). Each Project Company hereby consents to the use of the Shared Premises Property Rights by the Project Companies and Manager pursuant to this Agreement, including without limitation, where such Shared Premises Property Rights affect, or otherwise touch and concern, other real property interests or estates held by such Project Company so long as such use is consistent with the requirements of this Agreement and the rights of the Parties hereunder. To the extent that any Shared Premises or Shared Premises Property Rights are not held specifically by the Project Companies in accordance with their Proportionate Shares, the Parties shall nonetheless share rights and obligations with respect to such Shared Premises and Shared Premises Property Rights in accordance with their Proportionate Shares. (c) The Commonly Held Easements are the separate property of each applicable Project Company. For all purposes under this Agreement, the Project Companies shall use the Commonly Held Easements and share (in accordance with their Proportionate Share as indicated in Exhibit D) rights and obligations with respect to the Commonly Held Easements in the same manner as Shared Premises Property Rights and Shared Premises hereunder. Unless specifically stated otherwise, all references to Shared Premises Property Rights and Shared Premises shall be interpreted as including the Commonly Held Easements, 2.3 Shared Facilities. (a) The Project Companies plan to procure, install and construct, or have procured, installed and constructed, certain facilities for electrical transmission, interconnection, communications and other structures and facilities, as described with respect to all of the Project Companies on Exhibit C-1, with respect to solely Azul, Rojo and Verde on Exhibit C-2, and with respect to solely Rojo and Verde on Exhibit C-3, which may be altered or reconstructed in accordance with this Agreement, for shared use by the Project Companies (collectively, the "Shared Facilities"). (b) Each Project Company shall own and hold an undivided interest in the Shared Facilities jointly with the other Project Companies, as tenants in common in proportion to their Proportionate Shares as set forth on Exhibit D for the benefit, operation and use of its respective Project as provided herein. (c) The Shared Facilities do not include equipment, materials or other property (if any) identified in Exhibits C-2, C-3 and C-4 as the sole property of any Project Company or other Person. (d) Each Project Company may use the Shared Facilities only to transmit electrical energy from its Project to the Point of Interconnection. No Project Company will provide any interconnection or transmission services or rights to any other Project Company. 2.4 Access to the Shared Premises and Shared Facilities. (a) By Project Companies. Subject to the conditions and additional rights described below, each Project Company and any Secured Party of such Project Company shall have access to and the right to enter onto the Shared Premises and the Shared Facilities to the extent reasonably necessary for (i) inspection of such Shared Premises and the Shared Facilities located thereon, without unduly interfering with the normal operations of the other Project Companies or the Manager and otherwise subject to the terms and conditions set forth in this Agreement, (ii) construction or Operation and Maintenance of the Shared Facilities in the event the Manager fails to do so, in accordance with the terms hereof, or (iii) for ingress and egress to and from, and for maintenance or repair of, the Shared Facilities in the event of an Emergency and the failure or unavailability of the Manager or its representatives to respond timely to such Emergency. Except in the event of an Emergency, the accessing Project Company shall give the other Project Companies and the Manager at least forty-eight (48) hours prior notice of its intent to enter upon the Shared Premises (said notice may be by telephone, e-mail, or any other recognized electronic means in addition to any other methods of notice authorized herein). In the event of an Emergency, prior notice is not required, but the Project Company shall give notice of entry onto the Shared Premises as soon as reasonably practicable thereafter. Any Project Company entering on the Shared Premises or accessing the Shared Facilities shall follow all written safety and security procedures adopted by the Project Companies and/or the Manager with respect to the Shared Premises and/or the Shared Facilities or otherwise applicable to the Shared Premises and/or the Shared Facilities under any binding lease, easement, franchise, or crossing agreement benefitting or burdening such Shared Premises where the terms thereof have been made available to the entering Project Company. Notwithstanding the above, if any part of the Shared Premises is also subject to a lease agreement, easement, license or other similar agreement with a Project Company for its respective Project, the Project Company may enter upon any of the Shared Premises that is part of such Project Company's rights pursuant to any such lease agreement, easement, license or other similar agreement without the need to give prior notice or obtain consent as provided in this Section 2.4(b) unless such entry is with respect to the Shared Facilities located thereon and then only to the extent set forth above. (b) By Manager. The Manager shall have access to the Shared Premises and Shared Facilities at any time for purposes of complying with its obligations set forth in this Agreement, including (i) inspection of such Shared Premises and the Shared Facilities located thereon, without unduly interfering with the normal operations of the Project Companies and otherwise subject to the terms and conditions set forth in this Agreement, (ii) construction or Operation and Maintenance of the Shared Facilities in accordance with the terms hereof, or (iii) for ingress and egress to and from, and for maintenance or repair of, the Shared Facilities. The Manager shall follow all written safety and security procedures adopted by the Project Companies with respect to the Shared Premises or otherwise applicable to the Shared Premises under any binding lease, easement, franchise or crossing agreement benefitting or burdening such Shared Premises where the terms thereof have been made available to the Manager. (c) By Secured Parties. A Secured Party of a Project Company shall have the right to enter onto the Shared Premises for the purposes described in Section 2.4(a)(i) and, in connection with or following the exercise of remedies by the Secured Party under its Security Documents, for the other purposes described in Section 2.4(a), in each case upon five (5) Business Days' advance written notice of its entry delivered to the Manager and the other Project Companies; provided that such right of entry shall be limited to normal business hours except in the case of an Emergency. Any Secured Party so entering on the Shared Premises or accessing the Shared Facilities shall (i) follow all written safety and security procedures and other site regulations of the Project Companies and/or the Manager with respect to the Shared Premises and/or the Shared Facilities or otherwise applicable to the Shared Premises and/or the Shared Facilities under any binding lease, easement, franchise or crossing agreement benefitting or burdening such Shared Premises where the terms thereof have been made available to the entering Project Company that is a debtor of such Project Company, and (ii) not unduly interfere with the normal operations of the Project Companies and the Manager thereon. 2.5 No Interference. Each Project Company's use of the Shared Premises and the Shared Facilities shall comply with the terms of the Shared Premises Property Rights and shall not interfere with the use and enjoyment by any other Project Company of its respective rights in such Shared Premises or Shared Facilities, subject to all the terms and provisions of this Agreement. Each of the Project Companies shall cooperate in good faith to accommodate each other Project Company's use of the Shared Premises and the Shared Facilities for the benefit of such other Project Company's Project. Subject to the first sentence of this Section 2.5, the use of the Shared Premises and the Shared Facilities by the Project Companies pursuant to and in accordance with the terms of this Agreement will not, separately or in the aggregate, be deemed to constitute an overburdening of the Shared Premises or the Shared Facilities or any portion of either of them. 2.6 Construction of Shared Facilities. (a) Construction of Shared Facilities. The Manager shall procure, install and construct the Shared Facilities on behalf of, and as agent of, the Project Companies pursuant to the EPC Contract and shall, immediately upon the passage of title to the Shared Facilities to Manager under the EPC Contract, assign and convey, and does hereby assign and convey, title to the Shared Facilities (and any associated rights under the EPC Contract, including applicable warranty rights in and to such Shared Facilities) to the Project Companies, as tenants in common in proportion to their respective Proportionate Shares, to be held pursuant to this Agreement. (b) Construction Documents. The Shared Facilities shall be constructed pursuant to design and construction plans and specifications attached to the EPC Contract (the "Construction Documents"), which are hereby approved by all Parties. The EPC Contract will also provide for the acquisition of the spare parts described on Exhibit X-17 thereto, the cost of which shall be considered a Shared Facilities Construction Cost. Manager shall diligently commence and complete construction of the Shared Facilities in accordance with the approved Construction Documents, applicable Governmental Requirements and Good Utility Practice. Manager shall use commercially reasonable efforts to have all Project Companies and the Manager identified as beneficiaries of the warranties and indemnities obtained with respect to the Shared Facilities. Manager shall not be required to obtain the consent of any Project Company to any change to the Construction Documents that is consistent with the previously approved Construction Documents in all material respects. The Project Companies and Manager shall coordinate construction of the Projects and the Shared Facilities to minimize disruption to their respective construction activities and schedules and to ensure continued access in and to the Properties as necessary. (c) Payment of Shared Facilities Construction Costs. Each Project Company shall be responsible for its Proportionate Share of the Shared Facilities Construction Costs. Upon commencement of construction under the Construction Documents, each Project Company shall reimburse Manager for its Proportionate Share of the Shared Facilities Construction Costs incurred by Manager prior to commencement of construction under the Construction Documents, and shall thereafter reimburse Manager for its Proportionate Share of Shared Facilities Construction Costs monthly, within thirty (30) days after receipt of an invoice from the Manager specifying in reasonable detail the amounts incurred which are subject to reimbursement. Amounts (including amounts determined to be due after resolution of a Dispute) that are not paid within such thirty (30) day period shall accrue interest at the Default Interest Rate until paid. In the event of any dispute regarding the reimbursement of the Shared Facilities Construction Costs between the Parties which cannot be resolved within sixty (60) days after reasonably diligent good faith efforts, any Party may seek arbitration of the Dispute pursuant to the provisions of Article 13 below. Notwithstanding the foregoing, in no event shall any dispute regarding allocation of costs require the Manager to delay or suspend construction of any Shared Facilities. (d) Monitoring and Step-In Rights. (i) The Project Companies shall have the right, each at its sole cost and expense, to monitor the construction of the Shared Facilities, and Manager shall afford reasonable access to the Project Companies for such purpose. Any Project Company exercising such monitoring right shall not interfere with the construction activities of Manager and shall comply with all of Manager's workplace safety and security requirements. (ii) If an "Owner Event of Default" (as defined in the EPC Contract) has occurred and is continuing under the EPC Contract, and Manager has not cured such Owner Event of Default within ten (10) days after its occurrence, in the case of an Owner Event of Default that can be cured by the payment of money, or thirty (30) days after its occurrence, in the case of an Owner Event of Default that cannot be cured solely by the payment of money, any Project Company may, upon two (2) days' notice to Manager and the other Project Companies, cure such Owner Event of Default on behalf of Manager and take such other actions as may be reasonably necessary to preserve the Parties' rights under the EPC Contract. The other Project Companies shall reimburse the Project Company exercising such rights for their respective Proportionate Shares of all costs and expenses incurred by such Project Company in exercising such rights and curing the Owner Event of Default; provided, however, that such reimbursement shall not release Manager from any obligations or liabilities it might have hereunder in connection with such Owner Event of Default. (iii) In the event Manager fails to commence construction of the Shared Facilities by August 1, 2017, and to diligently prosecute such construction to completion, and such failure is not remedied within thirty (30) days following written notice thereof from any Project Company, then such Project Company may, without any obligation to do so, elect to step in and commence and/or complete construction of the Shared Facilities pursuant to the approved Construction Documents and this Agreement (such Project Company shall become the "Substitute Constructing Party"). A Substitute Constructing Party shall provide at least ten (10) Business Days' advance written notice to the Manager, the other Project Companies, and to any Secured Party providing financing to the Manager or any Project Company, prior to its commencing and/or completing construction of the Shared Facilities pursuant to the approved Construction Documents and this Agreement. Subject to any cure rights of any Secured Parties, following the exercise by the Substitute Constructing Party of its step-in rights with respect to the Shared Facilities, all provisions of this Agreement applicable to the Manager as the Party constructing the Shared Facilities shall apply to the Substitute Constructing Party's construction and completion of the Shared Facilities. The Manager shall provide all assistance and cooperation as the Substitute Constructing Party shall reasonably require to complete the Shared Facilities, including without limitation, assignment to the Substitute Constructing Party of all design contracts, engineering contracts, subcontracts, materials contracts, supply contracts and other contracts and agreements to which the Manager is a party in connection with the installation of the Shared Facilities ("Project Contracts"). Manager shall use commercially reasonable efforts to cause the foregoing Project Company step-in rights to be included in the Project Contracts for purposes of recognition by the counterparties to the Project Contracts of a Project Company's step-in rights hereunder. (e) Requested Modifications to Shared Facilities. In the event (i) a Project Company desires that Manager design, install or construct as part of the Shared Facilities any improvements or installations, or make changes to the Construction Documents (other than to correct inaccuracies in previously approved Construction Documents), in each case, that primarily serve such Project Company's Project, (ii) such improvements, installations or changes would not otherwise be included by the Manager in the Shared Facilities, (iii) the Manager is satisfied in its reasonable discretion that such additional improvements or installations will not adversely affect any other Project, and (iv) such Project Company has fully funded the cost of such improvements or installations, as estimated by Manager, Manager will design, install and construct such additional improvements or installations that otherwise would not be part of the Shared Facilities. Manager shall be responsible for determining the final actual cost of such improvements or installations and to the extent the costs incurred by Manager exceed those funded by the applicable Project Company, such Project Company shall promptly fund the difference in such amount to Manager. If Manager determines that the applicable Project Company funded an amount in excess of the actual cost of such improvements or installations, Manager shall promptly refund such excess amount to the Project Company. 2.7 Additional Premises Rights or Facilities. (a) Approval of Additional Premises Rights or Facilities. To the extent that any additional premises or rights in premises (other than the Shared Premises Property Rights existing as of the Agreement Date) that relate to the Shared Facilities or operation thereof (the "Additional Premises Rights") or any additional facilities, improvements, modifications, or upgrades of facilities that relate to the Shared Facilities or operation thereof ("Additional Facilities") (i) are required in order to construct, use, operate, maintain or repair the Shared Facilities, (ii) are required by any Project Company for the construction, use, operation, maintenance or repair of its Project, or (iii) are needed or would materially benefit, in the reasonable belief of the Manager, the interconnection or operation of the Projects collectively, a Project Company or the Manager, as applicable, may give written notice to the other Parties of such requirement, with a reasonable explanation why such Additional Premises Rights and/or Additional Facilities are needed and demonstrating that such Additional Premises Rights and/or Additional Facilities will not, taken as a whole, have an adverse effect on the Shared Facilities or any Project. (1) Each Project Company shall, within thirty (30) days after receiving such notice, notify the Manager and the other Project Companies in writing of its election to participate or not to participate in such Additional Premises Rights and/or Additional Facilities, as applicable. Failure to notify the other Project Company of its election to participate shall be deemed an election not to participate. (2) If acquisition of the Additional Premises Rights and/or Additional Facilities is approved by all of the Project Companies, they shall be acquired in the name of all of the Project Companies as tenants in common and shall become Shared Premises Property Rights and/or Shared Facilities, as applicable, hereunder. (3) Following acquisition of any Additional Premises Rights and/or Additional Facilities, the Parties will amend Exhibits A, B and C as necessary to reflect such new Shared Premises Property Rights and/or Shared Facilities. (b) Disapproved Additional Premises Rights or Additional Facilities. If any proposed Additional Premises Rights or Additional Facilities are not approved pursuant to the provisions of Section 2.7(a) above, but the requirements of Section 2.7(c) below are satisfied and any additional facilities, improvements, modifications or upgrades are constructed and installed in accordance with Governmental Requirements and Good Utility Practice, then nothing herein shall prevent a Project Company from acquiring such property rights ("Disapproved Additional Premises Rights") or installing such additional facilities, improvements, modifications or upgrades ("Disapproved Additional Facilities") in its own name. Any such Disapproved Additional Premises Rights and Disapproved Additional Facilities shall not be deemed Shared Premises Property Rights or Shared Facilities hereunder. (c) Requirements of All Additional Premises Rights and Additional Facilities. No Additional Premises Rights (including any Disapproved Additional Premises Rights) shall be acquired by any Project Company, and no Additional Facilities (including any Disapproved Additional Facilities) may be acquired, constructed or installed by any Project Company, if such acquisition, construction or installation could reasonably be expected to (i) result in an Emergency, (ii) violate the terms of this Agreement, any existing Shared Premises Property Right, the Co-Tenancy Agreement, any Interconnection Agreement, any Power Purchase Agreement or any Security Documents, or (iii) have any more than an insignificant adverse effect on the operation, performance, reliability or maintenance costs of any Project (except as may be agreed by the Party owning such Project), or the operation, performance, reliability or Operation and Maintenance costs of the Shared Facilities; provided, however, that if requested by the Project Company proposing to acquire, construct or install the Additional Premises Rights or the Additional Facilities, a Project Company will use commercially reasonable efforts to obtain any necessary consents under the Security Documents related to its Project to allow the acquisition, construction and/or installation of such Additional Premises Rights or Additional Facilities. 2.8 Covenants Running with the Land. The covenants of the Project Companies made in this Agreement shall be deemed to be covenants running with and binding upon the land pursuant to applicable law for the duration of the term of this Agreement and shall bind and benefit all current and future owners of the lands bound and benefited by this Agreement, including the Shared Premises, Shared Premises Property Rights, the Additional Premises Rights and the Property. 2.9 Liens. No Party shall, directly or indirectly, create, incur or permit to exist any lien on the Shared Premises, the Shared Premises Property Rights or the Shared Facilities, either as a whole or in a Party's undivided interest therein, except for (a) liens for financing purposes as provided in Section 8.3, and (b) Permitted Encumbrances. If any lien not permitted under the previous sentence attaches to any of the Shared Premises, the Shared Premises Property Rights or the Shared Facilities, or if a Party receives notice of any such lien, the Party whose actual or alleged act or omission resulted in such lien shall cause such lien to be released and removed of record within thirty (30) days of such attachment or notice. Failure of a Party to remove such lien as required under this Section 2.9 shall entitle each other Party to cause such lien to be removed and the costs thereof shall be promptly reimbursed by the Party responsible hereunder for removal of such lien. Notwithstanding the forgoing, nothing herein shall require a Project Company to remove a lien that relates to its separate property interest in property that is also located on or within the Shared Premises other than a Shared Premises Property Right hereunder, if such lien relates to such Project Company's rights in and to that portion of the Shared Premises by virtue of a separate lease, easement or license agreement and that is not a Shared Premises Property Right hereunder. ARTICLE 3 PAYMENT OF O&M EXPENSES 3.1 Expenses of Operation and Maintenance of the Shared Facilities and Shared Premises. The Operation and Maintenance of the Shared Facilities and Shared Premises shall be performed in accordance with the requirements set forth in Article 5 below. The expenses of such Operation and Maintenance shall be allocated among the Project Companies and paid as provided in this Article 3. (a) Shared O&M Expenses. Each Project Company shall be responsible for and shall pay its Proportionate Share of the expenses and liabilities relating to the Operation and Maintenance of the Shared Facilities, including all allocable payments under the O&M Agreement, all FERC compliance costs, NERC compliance costs, costs of compliance with other Governmental Requirements, costs of labor and materials and accounting, general and administrative costs (collectively, "Shared O&M Expenses"). (b) Step-In Rights; Indemnity. If any Project Company fails to pay its share of Shared O&M Expenses as and when due, including any amounts that may be due to the Manager hereunder, then, upon at least five (5) days' written notice to the defaulting Project Company, one or more of the other Project Companies may, but shall not be obligated to, advance any amounts which such defaulting Project Company failed to pay, and such defaulting Project Company shall promptly reimburse the Project Company or Project Companies making such advances upon demand for all such amounts advanced on behalf of the defaulting Project Company, together with interest thereon from the date advanced to the date repaid at the Default Interest Rate. 3.2 Invoicing, Late Payments. (a) The Manager shall be responsible for invoicing each Project Company for its applicable Proportionate Share of the Shared O&M Expenses relating to the Shared Facilities. Each such invoice shall be payable by the invoiced Project Company within fifteen (15) days after receipt of an invoice, with backup documentation, from the Manager setting forth the amount that is due. If a Project Company disputes the invoiced amount, it shall nonetheless pay the disputed amount, and shall refer the issue for resolution in accordance with provisions of Article 13. Any disputed amount that is finally determined by dispute resolution pursuant to Article 13 or by mutual agreement to have been improperly invoiced shall be promptly refunded to the Project Company. All sums not paid when due shall thereafter bear interest at the Default Interest Rate. Each Project Company shall have the right to audit, and receive supporting documentation for, any expenses or other amounts required to be paid by such Project Company hereunder. (b) In addition to the reports under Section 5.7, within thirty (30) days after the end of each calendar year, the Manager shall provide the Project Companies an annual statement of all actual Shared O&M Expenses during the previous calendar year, all payments made by each Project Company on account of Shared O&M Expenses, and a reconciliation of the amounts paid by each such Project Company against such Project Company's Proportionate Share of the actual Shared O&M Expenses during such calendar year. If any Project Company's share of such Shared O&M Expenses exceeds the amounts paid by such Project Company, such Project Company shall pay the amount of such difference to the Manager as part of the next monthly invoice. If any Project Company's share of such Shared O&M Expenses is less than the amounts paid by such Project Company, the Manager shall credit the amount of such overpayment by such Project Company against future invoiced amounts from the Manager until such credit is exhausted. 3.3 Property Taxes and Assessments. The Manager shall allocate all property taxes on the attributable Shared Premises Property Rights and Shared Facilities, whether payable as owner or lessee, to the Project Companies in proportion to their respective Proportionate Shares in the Shared Facilities. If desired by the Manager, or by a Supermajority in Interest of the affected Project Companies, the Manager shall contest the validity or amount of any assessments or taxes attributable to the Shared Premises Property Rights or Shared Facilities for which the Parties are responsible hereunder by appropriate legal proceedings. Such costs shall be deemed a Shared O&M Expense and shall be reimbursable by the Project Companies regardless of whether included in the Approved Shared Facilities O&M Budget. In the event that a Project Company locates its separately owned non-Shared Facilities equipment or property on any Shared Premises Property Rights or otherwise uses Shared Premises Property for its private use pursuant to Section 4.14, Manager shall in its reasonable discretion determine an equitable allocation to such Project Company of property taxes applicable to such Shared Premises Property Rights. 3.4 Costs of Repair Work. The Manager shall charge the costs of Repairs of Shared Facilities, and for other work or services provided by the Manager, including costs paid to third parties, at the actual cost to the Manager therefor. 3.5 Shared Facilities O&M Budget. (a) Upon Substantial Completion of the Shared Facilities and no later than sixty (60) days prior to the beginning of each calendar year thereafter during the term hereof, the Manager shall prepare and submit to the Parties a proposed budget for Operation and Maintenance of the Shared Premises and Shared Facilities for the following calendar year, or the portions of the calendar year remaining after Substantial Completion of the Shared Facilities (each, a "Shared Facilities O&M Budget"), which budget shall include the estimated cost of all anticipated Shared O&M Expenses during the following year; provided that, such Shared Facilities O&M Budget shall not include the cost of construction of the Shared Facilities or any Additional Facilities, which costs shall be governed by the applicable provisions of Article 2. The Shared Facilities O&M Budget shall set forth the respective amounts allocated to the Project Companies in accordance with Exhibit D hereto. When approved pursuant to subparagraph (b) below, the Shared Facilities O&M Budget shall be the "Approved Shared Facilities O&M Budget" for such year. (b) The Shared Facilities O&M Budget shall be subject to the approval of all of the Project Companies (such approval not to be unreasonably withheld); provided, however, that the portion of the Shared Facilities O&M Budget reflecting the cost and expenses to be paid pursuant to the O&M Agreement and any other third party operations and maintenance agreement entered into by Manager consistently with this Agreement are deemed approved Shared O&M Expenses hereunder. The Project Companies shall give their approval or disapproval of the Shared Facilities O&M Budget no later than thirty (30) days after receipt thereof from the Manager; provided that, pending approval, Manager may operate and maintain the Shared Facilities based on the Approved Shared Facilities O&M Budget for the previous calendar year, as adjusted by the Inflation Adjustment Factor and further increased an additional ten percent (10%) in each budget category. (c) Notwithstanding anything to the contrary herein, the Manager shall be permitted to, in its reasonable discretion, incur, or cause the incurrence, on behalf of the Project Companies, (i) costs and expenses for the Operation and Maintenance of Shared Facilities in a given year in amounts that exceed the Approved Shared Facilities O&M Budget by up to (but not more than) twenty-five percent (25%), and (ii) any expenses needed to respond to an Emergency to ensure safe operation of the Shared Facilities or to return the Shared Facilities from any outage, including, if applicable, pursuant to Section 5.2(g), and such excess expenses shall be deemed approved Shared O&M Expenses hereunder. 3.6 Other Expenses Caused By Parties. Notwithstanding the provisions of this Agreement, any costs, claims, loss or other liability to third parties arising from the actions or inactions of a Party in violation or breach of the covenants herein or the provisions of any Shared Premises Property Right, the Co-Tenancy Agreement, the Interconnection Agreement or a Power Purchase Agreement shall be the responsibility of such Party to the extent not covered by the policies of insurance required under Article 7 below, provided that such Party shall pay all deductibles due under such policies with respect thereto. 3.7 Rights of Other Party for Non-Payment. If a Party (a "Non-Paying Party") fails to timely make any required payment of amounts due under Article 2 or this Article 3, one or more of the other Parties may make such payment on behalf of such Non-Paying Party and the amount so paid shall be immediately due and payable from the Non-Paying Party to such other Party or Parties, together with interest at the Default Interest Rate from the date paid until repaid to such other Party or Parties. ARTICLE 4 OTHER RIGHTS AND OBLIGATIONS OF THE PARTIES 4.1 Maximum Capacity of Projects. The maximum capacity ("Maximum Capacity") shall mean (subject to this Section 4.1), with respect to any Project, the maximum net generation capacity, in MW, of each Project, set forth in Exhibit E, which Maximum Capacity may be changed only in accordance with this Agreement, the Interconnection Agreement and the Co-Tenancy Agreement, provided that the combined Maximum Capacity of the Projects shall not exceed the maximum net generation capacity of the Projects as measured at the Point of Interconnection, as identified and described in Appendix C to the Interconnection Agreement. Each Project Company shall be authorized to construct its Project with a nameplate capacity of up to, but not in excess of, the Maximum Capacity as measured at the Point of Interconnection for such Project as set forth on Exhibit E. 4.2 Maintenance and Repair of Projects. Without limiting each Project Company's obligations under the Co-Tenancy Agreement or the Interconnection Agreement, each Project Company shall, at its sole cost and expense, (a) maintain in good working order and repair at all times each part of its Project which connects with or may affect the Shared Facilities or the Shared Premises, (b) comply with all of its obligations under the Conditional Use Permits where noncompliance may affect the Shared Facilities or the Shared Premises, (c) comply with all applicable requirements of NERC and any Governmental Requirements relating to the Shared Facilities and Shared Premises, (d) comply with all applicable easements, licenses, encroachment permits, and crossing agreements pertinent to or affecting the Shared Facilities or the Shared Premises, and (e) comply with all curtailment orders received by the Project Company from the Manager. 4.3 Termination or Modification of Any Shared Premises Property Right. No Project Company shall terminate any Shared Premises Property Rights nor permit any Shared Premises Property Rights to expire prior to the expiration of this Agreement without the prior written consent of all of the Project Companies. Further, no Project Company shall (i) subject to the following subsection (ii), modify or amend any of the Shared Premises Property Rights in any way without the prior written consent of all Project Companies, or (ii) modify or amend any of the Shared Premises Property Rights in a manner that materially, adversely affects a Project Company without the prior written consent of that Project Company; provided, however, that if a Project Company intends to abandon or cease operation of its Project, it may do so only in accordance with Article 9 below. 4.4 Standard of Performance. Each Party shall perform its obligations under this Agreement (i) in accordance with all requirements of this Agreement, all Governmental Requirements, Good Utility Practice, the Shared Premises Property Rights, the Co-Tenancy Agreement, and the Interconnection Agreement and any applicable requirements of FERC, NERC, the CAISO, and the Participating Transmission Owner, and (ii) in a manner that is (A) non-discriminatory, and (B) attempts to maximize the delivery of energy and energy-related products from the Projects to the Point of Interconnection at a reasonable cost. 4.5 Party Representatives. On or promptly after the Agreement Date, each Party shall by written notice to the other Parties designate an individual representative of such Party and an alternate (the "Party Representative") whose written instructions, requests, and decisions will be binding upon such Party in all matters concerning this Agreement, except that the Party's Representative shall not have the authority to amend this Agreement. Each Party shall have the right to change such Party's Representative at any time and from time to time by written notice to the other Parties. 4.6 No Warranties. No Party makes any warranty, express or implied with respect to the Shared Facilities, the Shared Premises, the Additional Facilities, or Qualified Replacement Components. THE FOREGOING EXCLUSION OF ALL WARRANTIES BY EACH PARTY INCLUDES IMPLIED WARRANTIES OF SUITABILITY AND FITNESS FOR A PARTICULAR PURPOSE. 4.7 Withdrawal of Party. Subject to the provisions of this Section 4.7, if a Project Company determines that it will cease operation of or otherwise abandon its Project or not require any Shared Premises Property Rights or Shared Facilities hereunder, such Project Company shall have the right to withdraw from this Agreement, subject to the requirements of Article 9, provided written notice thereof is given to the other Parties. Following such permitted withdrawal, the withdrawing Project Company shall have no further right of access to or use of the Shared Premises or the Shared Facilities. No such withdrawal shall release the withdrawing Project Company from any indemnification or reimbursement obligations that arise prior to the effective date of its withdrawal, including its obligation to pay its Proportionate Share of Shared Facilities Construction Costs, Shared O&M Expenses and all applicable costs described in Sections 9.2, 9.3 and 9.4. A Project Company may not withdraw from this Agreement until after completion of construction of the initial Shared Facilities. 4.8 No Waste or Nuisance. To the extent that a Party has the authority under this Agreement (or any applicable third party agreement) to prevent such actions or inactions, no Party will use or permit the use of the Shared Facilities or Shared Facilities Services in any manner that would create waste or nuisance, or that would increase the rate, or jeopardize the issuance or maintenance, of any insurance policy relating to the Shared Facilities or any Project, nor otherwise conduct or cause to be conducted operations on its Properties which would have similar effects on, or otherwise damage or interfere with, the Shared Facilities or any other Project. The Parties will at all times while conducting their respective operations make commercially reasonable efforts to minimize the impact of such operations and activities upon the other Parties. 4.9 No Public Access. The Parties agree that, except as required to comply with the terms of a Shared Premise Property Right or unless so ordered by a Governmental Authority, there will be no general public access to the Shared Premises or the Shared Facilities. The Parties shall undertake to cooperate in enforcing such requirement for limiting access to the Shared Premises and the Shared Facilities, including establishing and enforcing procedures for safety and security. 4.10 Reserved. 4.11 Competing Ventures. Any Party may engage in or possess an interest in other business ventures of any nature and description, independently or with others, including but not limited to the ownership, financing, leasing, management, syndication, investment, brokerage and development of real property (including real property of the same type and nature as the Projects), and no Party shall have any right by virtue of this Agreement in and to such independent ventures or to the income or profits derived therefrom. 4.12 FERC Approvals. If required by law, this Agreement will be filed for acceptance with FERC. Promptly after the Agreement Date and after any amendment to the Agreement that is required to be filed at FERC, the Parties will cooperate in the preparation of a filing by the Manager, on behalf of the Project Companies, acceptable to all Parties to seek acceptance by FERC of the Agreement or such amendment and the Manager, on behalf of the Project Companies, will file the Agreement or such amendment for acceptance by FERC. Each of the Parties agrees that it will cooperate in the preparation of such filings and as necessary to address any issues raised by FERC in connection with the filing for acceptance of the Agreement or such amendment. Subject to the terms and conditions set forth herein, the Parties agree to execute and deliver all documents reasonably necessary for this Agreement to comply with FERC requirements. 4.13 Conflict Among Agreements. In the event of any conflict between the Manager's obligations under this Agreement and the Co-Tenancy Agreement or Interconnection Agreement, the terms of the Co-Tenancy Agreement or Interconnection Agreement shall prevail. The Manager shall notify the Project Companies in writing if it becomes aware of any such conflict and the Parties shall discuss whether amendments to this Agreement are necessary to address such matters. 4.14 Separate Use. Provided there is no interference with the use of Shared Facilities, and subject to the terms of this Agreement and such other terms and conditions as Manager may require in its reasonable discretion, Manager shall permit any Project Company to locate its separate non-Shared Facilities equipment or property on the Shared Premises Property Rights if reasonably necessary for the construction or operation of such Project Company's Project. 4.15 SCADA Access. Each Project Company shall be permitted access to SCADA data regarding the PG&E Tranquillity Switching Station and its own Project. The Manager shall be permitted full access to SCADA data, including the PG&E Tranquillity Switching Station and all Projects. The Project Companies are not permitted access to SCADA data regarding the Projects of other Project Companies. 4.16 Line Losses. Line losses on the Shared Facilities will be calculated in accordance with the applicable provisions of the CAISO Tariff; provided, however, that following the connection of the first Project to the Shared Facilities, any Project Company ("Subsequent Project Company") connecting a subsequent Project (a "Subsequent Project") to the Shared Facilities will be responsible for all incremental line losses attributable to such Project to the extent further provided in this Section 4.16, if and to the extent that the allocation of incremental line losses to such Subsequent Project as proposed to the CAISO in accordance with the provisions of this Section is accepted by the CAISO. Prior to connecting a Subsequent Project to the Shared Facilities, the Subsequent Project Company will cooperate with existing Project Companies connected to the Shared Facilities, the Manager, and the CAISO to agree on adjustments to the Project meters for all Projects and other arrangements (collectively, a "Metering and Line Loss Scheme") that are designed to minimize or eliminate the imposition of any incremental line losses on any such existing Projects as a result of connection of the Subsequent Project to the Shared Facilities by allocating such incremental line losses to the Subsequent Project. As early as reasonably practicable (and at least 120 days or such other period as may be necessary to comply with CAISO metering requirements) prior to the connection of such Subsequent Project, the Subsequent Project Company will provide to the existing Project Companies and the Manager any documents and information that are necessary or appropriate to develop the Metering and Line Loss Scheme. The existing Project Companies and the Manager shall review the documents and information provided by the Subsequent Project Company and shall provide any comments to the Subsequent Project Company within twenty (20) days of receipt. The existing Project Companies, the Subsequent Project Company and the Manager shall cooperate, and if necessary will meet and confer, to reasonably resolve any disagreements as quickly as possible and complete a metering document package that incorporates the Metering and Line Loss Scheme as provided in this Section 4.16. The Manager shall submit the metering documentation package to the CAISO to establish such a Metering and Line Loss Scheme in time to allow connection of the Subsequent Project as scheduled (such scheme, the "Approved Metering and Line Loss Scheme"). The existing Project Companies, the Subsequent Project Company and the Manager shall cooperate in the event that the CAISO requests more information with respect to the Approved Metering and Line Loss Scheme, and the Manager shall respond to the CAISO as quickly as reasonably possible with such information. Additionally, the existing Project Companies, the Subsequent Project Company and the Manager shall reasonably cooperate to make revisions to the Approved Metering Line Loss Scheme requested by CAISO, where such revisions are consistent with the allocation of incremental line losses to the Subsequent Project Company, and the Manager shall respond to the CAISO as quickly as reasonably possible concerning such revisions. However, in the event that the CAISO does not approve the allocation of incremental line losses to the Subsequent Project Company in the Approved Metering and Line Loss Scheme, as such may be revised pursuant to the preceding sentence, and the CAISO requires modification to the allocation of losses, the Project Companies will accept the allocation of losses determined by the CAISO in accordance with the CAISO Tariff and such modified Metering and Line Loss Scheme approved by the CAISO (the "Modified Metering and Line Loss Scheme"), even if such Modified Metering and Line Loss Scheme allocates to the existing Project Companies some of the incremental line losses resulting from the connection of the Subsequent Project. The Subsequent Project Company shall not owe any compensation to the existing Project Companies on account of incremental line losses as a result of interconnecting to the Shared Facilities, it being agreed that all incremental line losses are addressed in the Approved Metering and Line Loss Scheme or the Modified Metering and Line Loss Scheme, whichever is adopted. ARTICLE 5 OPERATION AND MAINTENANCE OF THE SHARED PREMISES AND THE SHARED FACILITIES 5.1 In General. (a) The Manager shall perform, or cause the performance of, the Operation and Maintenance of the Shared Facilities in accordance with this Agreement. The costs and expenses incurred to maintain the Shared Facilities, whether by Manager or a third party, shall be incurred and shared in accordance with Article 3. Each of the Project Companies shall cooperate with the Manager in the performance of the Operation and Maintenance of the Shared Facilities. (b) The Manager shall have the right to enter into an operations and maintenance agreement ("O&M Agreement") with a third party operation and maintenance provider to perform some or all of such services (provided that, absent good cause and subject to compliance with NERC requirements and Governmental Requirements, only one operation and maintenance provider shall be engaged to perform such services), and payments by the Manager under the O&M Agreement will be Shared O&M Expenses as provided in Section 3.1(a). The O&M Agreement shall provide that if the operator under the O&M Agreement is not the same Person providing operations and maintenance services to all of the Projects, then all spare parts related to the Shared Facilities shall be stored on the Shared Premises or an alternate location as mutually agreed by the Parties. 5.2 Specific Authority. Without limiting the authority of the Manager pursuant to Section 5.1, but subject to the limitations of authority of the Manager in Section 5.3 below, the Manager shall have the power, without further consent or approval of the Parties: (a) To perform, or cause the performance of, the Operation and Maintenance of the Shared Facilities, including any Repairs subject to the requirements of Section 5.4 below. (b) Subject to Section 5.4, to negotiate, enter into, execute, acknowledge or amend agreements relating to the Operation and Maintenance of the Shared Facilities, provided that (i) no such actions would reasonably be expected to adversely affect the rights or privileges of the Parties except with respect to incurring additional expenses for the accounts of the Parties that are within the Approved Shared Facilities O&M Budget (and any amounts in excess thereof permitted under this Agreement) and (ii) the Manager shall provide each Party with copies of any such agreement promptly upon execution thereof; (c) To, or to cause a third party acting on its behalf to, (i) exercise all of the Project Companies' rights under the warranties with respect to the Shared Facilities, Additional Facilities or Repairs, as applicable; (ii) monitor and report to the other Project Companies concerning the remaining terms of any such warranties; (iii) perform such inspections as are reasonable to ensure that any final warranty work is not required prior to the expiration of any such warranty, and (iv) prepare and prosecute warranty claims, if reasonably necessary to enforce any such warranties; (d) To employ from time to time, at the expense of the Project Companies but subject to the Approved Shared Facilities O&M Budget, persons, firms or corporations to perform Operation and Maintenance of the Shared Facilities, including entering into an O&M Agreement; (e) To pay and collect amounts due in connection with the Shared Premises Property Rights and Shared Facilities, and to maintain one or more bank accounts wherein funds received by the Manager in connection with its duties hereunder shall be maintained; (f) To expend monies necessary for Operation and Maintenance in accordance with the Approved Shared Facilities O&M Budget (including any amounts in excess thereof permitted under this Agreement); (g) To commit to the expenditure of or spend such amounts for and on behalf of the Project Companies as are reasonably necessary to expedite Repairs to the Shared Facilities due to an Emergency up to and including Two Hundred Fifty-Thousand Dollars ($250,000.00) in the aggregate (including the costs of installation and expediting fees), provided that the Manager gives notice by facsimile or electronic mail to such Project Companies regarding the nature and amount of the expenditure as soon as reasonably practicable after the estimated amount of the expenditure is known by the Manager, but in any event no later than the time the Manager commits to the expenditure; (h) To negotiate with, and represent the Parties' interests before any Governmental Authority regarding property valuation and real property taxes (if any) related to the Shared Premises Property Rights and Shared Facilities; and (i) to execute, acknowledge and deliver any and all instruments and take such other steps as are reasonably necessary to effectuate the foregoing and as are consistent with the terms of this Agreement, including Section 5.3 and any other limitations set forth herein. 5.3 Limitation on Authority. 5.3.1 The Manager shall not, without the approval of all of the Project Companies: (a) Amend, modify or waive the terms of this Agreement or the Interconnection Agreement; (b) Create or cause to be created any lien or encumbrance on the Shared Premises Property Rights or the Shared Facilities, other than a Permitted Encumbrance; (c) Perform or omit to perform any act which would cause any person reasonably to believe that the Manager is authorized to bind the Project Companies, except as expressly permitted under this Agreement; (d) Sell, assign, mortgage, encumber, convey or otherwise transfer all or any portion of (i) the Shared Premises Property Rights or Shared Premises, or any interest or estate therein, or (ii) any Shared Facilities or any of the components thereof, other than the trade-in, sale or transfer of assets related thereto that are worn out, obsolete or no longer necessary or useful for the operation thereof; (e) Borrow funds on behalf of the Project Companies; or (f) Agree to any restrictions or limitations on the Shared Premises, the Shared Premises Property Rights, or the Shared Facilities that do not exist as of the Agreement Date; (g) Take any action to voluntarily and permanently remove any Shared Facilities from service, except to the extent they are being replaced with new or repaired facilities; or (h) Take any action which could reasonably be expected to have a material adverse effect on the ability of any Project Company to use the Shared Facilities or the Shared Premises Property Rights; except as required or permitted under this Agreement, the Interconnection Agreement or any Power Purchase Agreement. 5.3.2 The Manager shall not, without the approval of a Supermajority in Interest of the Project Companies: (a) Incur expenses except in accordance with this Agreement and/or the Approved Shared Facilities O&M Budget in any calendar year except as provided in this Agreement; (b) Except as provided in the Approved Shared Facilities O&M Budget or as provided in Sections 3.5(c) and 5.2(g), enter into any commitments, contracts or other agreements requiring expenditures in excess of One Hundred Thousand Dollars ($100,000.00) or with a duration of more than two (2) years except for (i) permitted expenditures in the case of an Emergency or as contemplated by the Approved Shared Facilities O&M Budget, or (ii) expenditures under the EPC Contract, the O&M Agreement or any approved amendment thereto; (c) Except as permitted under Sections 7.9 and 7.10, procure insurance coverage that is less than the coverage required under Article 7; or (d) Enter into or materially modify any agreement with any Affiliate of the Manager, other than agreements approved as part of the financing of the Projects, except on terms and conditions, including price, that are at least as favorable to the Project Companies as would be obtained from an unaffiliated third party. 5.4 Repairs. (a) The Manager shall have the right to replace or repair, or to cause to be replaced or repaired, any component or group of components of the Shared Facilities (i) with an aggregate cost of Five Hundred Thousand Dollars ($500,000.00) or less, or (ii) that must be repaired to ensure the continued safe operation of the Shared Facilities or to return the Shared Facilities to service, with a Qualified Replacement Component, consistent with Good Utility Practice (such repair or replacement work, "Repairs"). The Manager shall provide notice (the "Repairs Notice") in writing to the Project Companies of (i) any required Repairs, (ii) the proposed scope of the Repairs (the "Proposed Repairs"), including the material components to be used in such Proposed Repairs, which shall be Qualified Replacement Components, (iii) the estimated cost of the Repairs, and (iv) the anticipated commencement date and anticipated completion date of the work on such Repairs. No other notice of such Repairs shall be required except as such costs may be included in periodic financial and operating reports that may be required under this Agreement. Repairs with an aggregate cost greater than Five Hundred Thousand Dollars ($500,000.00) that are not required to ensure the continued safe operation of the Shared Facilities or to return the Shared Facilities to service, must be approved by all of the Project Companies (b) If the Manager performs any Repairs, it shall (i) limit, to the extent commercially reasonable and subject to Good Utility Practice, any interference with the use by the Project Companies of the Shared Facilities and Shared Premises during construction activities, (ii) except in the event of an Emergency, (A) schedule during an off-peak and/or low generation down-time period any required disconnection of the Shared Facilities to conduct construction activities in order to minimize any adverse impact on the Project Companies' Projects, and (B) provide at least thirty (30) days prior written notice of commencement of such construction activities together with a reasonably detailed description thereof, and (iii) comply with the requirements of the CAISO with respect thereto. (c) The Manager or another Project Company performing any Repairs (with respect to such Repairs) shall use commercially reasonable efforts to have all Project Companies and the Manager identified as beneficiaries of the warranties and indemnities obtained with respect to any Repairs. 5.5 Curtailment of Delivery. (a) The Project Companies shall have the right to curtail the output of their respective Projects from time to time as they see fit unless such curtailment would cause an Emergency. The Manager may, in accordance with this Section 5.5, direct the Project Companies to interrupt or reduce deliveries of electrical power through the Shared Facilities (i) when necessary for the Operation and Maintenance of the Shared Facilities; (ii) if the Manager determines, in its reasonable discretion, that interruption or reduction is necessary due to an Emergency; or (iii) at the direction of the Participating Transmission Owner or the CAISO pursuant to rights under the Interconnection Agreement. The Manager will use commercially reasonable efforts to give the Project Companies as much advance notice as is reasonably possible of such interruptions, reductions, or curtailments. The "Manager" under the Co-Tenancy Agreement shall promptly give the Manager written notice of any directions, instructions or orders from the Participating Transmission Owner or CAISO to interrupt or reduce deliveries of electrical power and, to the extent that action is required under the Co-Tenancy Agreement and/or Interconnection Agreement to implement any such interruptions, reductions or curtailments, the "Manager" under the Co-Tenancy Agreement shall take such actions as the Manager may request in connection with such interruptions, reductions or curtailments under this Agreement. (b) With respect to any interruption or reduction of deliveries of electrical power pursuant to clauses (i) or (ii) of Section 5.5(a), the Manager shall curtail delivery of energy generated during Trial Operations ("Test Power") from any Project that is still undergoing Trial Operations and has not reached commercial operation of its Project as provided in the Interconnection Agreement before curtailing delivery of electric power from any Project that has reached commercial operation under the Interconnection Agreement and shall limit the length of any such interruption or curtailment to the minimum extent and minimum time strictly necessary to correct the problem; provided that any additional interruption or reduction of deliveries beyond curtailment of Test Power shall follow the curtailment priority in Section 5.5(c) below. Any interruption or curtailment made pursuant to clause (i) of Section 5.5(a) shall be made to the extent commercially reasonable during periods of low or no solar generation or low energy prices. (c) In the event of any curtailment of interconnection services at the direction of CAISO or the Participating Transmission Owner, such curtailment shall be allocated to the Projects in the following manner, to the extent necessary, until such curtailment is achieved: (1) first, each Project Company (if any) that is delivering energy in excess of such Project Company's Maximum Capacity shall reduce deliveries down to such Project Company's Maximum Capacity; (2) second, each Project Company that is delivering Test Power shall reduce all such deliveries to the extent required to achieve such curtailment (including down to zero, if necessary); (3) third, as provided in and to the extent applicable under Section 5.5(d)(2), each such Project Company shall reduce all such deliveries until all required curtailment has been applied fully or any or all such Projects to which such curtailments relate under Section 5.5(d)(2) have been fully curtailed; and (4) fourth, subject to Section 5.5(d)(1), to the extent its Project has not already been fully curtailed, each Project Company shall reduce its energy deliveries so that they do not exceed an amount (the "Curtailed Output Cap") equal to (X) such Project Company's Maximum Capacity, minus (Y) the product of (i) the aggregate number of MWs then required for the Projects as a whole to curtail (after application of preceding clauses (c)(1), (2) (3), and 4) times (ii) such Project Company's Proportionate Share; provided that if during any relevant period of curtailment any Project Company is delivering energy at a level less than its Curtailed Output Cap (any such amount, a "Shortfall") either because such Project Company's Project is undergoing maintenance, has a forced outage, or other circumstance, then for so long as such Shortfall exists, each other Project Company may generate above such Project Company's Curtailed Output Cap by allocating among such other Project Companies the Shortfall on a pro rata basis in accordance with such other Project Companies' respective Proportionate Shares. (d) Notwithstanding the other provisions of this Section 5.5: (1) The Manager shall be authorized to curtail on a non-pro rata, but equitable and reasonable basis (as determined by the Manager in good faith) if (A) in spite of the Manager's good faith efforts to direct the Project Companies to comply with this Section 5.5, curtailment of deliveries from the Projects as directed by the CAISO or the Participating Transmission Owner is not otherwise achievable, or (B) such non-pro rata allocation is otherwise necessary to comply with the Interconnection Agreement or CAISO or the Participating Transmission Owner's direction, and, in each of the foregoing clauses (A) and (B), that such non-pro rata allocation will not result in a default under the Interconnection Agreement; and (2) To the extent that the need for any curtailment, interruption or reduction can be attributed to a particular Project Company's Project or portions of its Project or the failure of such Project to comply with the order to curtail or a default by such Project Company under this Agreement, the Interconnection Agreement, the Co-Tenancy Agreement or an applicable Power Purchase Agreement, or to the extent such Project Company's Project is the cause of an Emergency Condition or is directed by CAISO or the Participating Transmission Owner to curtail, then (A) all such curtailment shall be allocated to such Project Company and such Project Company will be responsible for all costs, liabilities and damages, including lost revenues, resulting from such curtailment (subject to the limitations in this Agreement), and (B) the Manager shall, to the extent possible, limit such interruption or reduction to such Project or such portions of the Project, as the case may be. (e) Each Project Company shall promptly implement such curtailment, interruption in, or reduction of, delivery as the Manager shall direct pursuant to this Section 5.5. In the event notice is impracticable or if a Project Company fails to promptly comply therewith, the Manager may take direct action to implement such curtailment, interruption, or reduction. A Project Company that fails to implement any such curtailment, interruption, or reduction, shall be responsible for all cost and expenses related thereto, including deviation or imbalance charges and penalties assessed by the CAISO. (f) In order to facilitate the scheduling of outages and disconnections of the Shared Facilities, each Project Company shall provide written notice to the Manager of any and all scheduled outage requirements set forth in its Power Purchase Agreement, if any, by the later of thirty (30) days after the Agreement Date or the date of execution of its Power Purchase Agreement. Thereafter on or before December 31 of each year, or such earlier date as required under the applicable Power Purchase Agreement, each Project Company shall provide to the Manager its forecasted scheduled outages of its Project for the next calendar year. The Manager shall make all commercially reasonable efforts to schedule Repairs in a manner that is consistent with the Project Company's scheduled outage requirements and the outage scheduling requirements of the Interconnection Agreement. 5.6 Disconnection of Shared Facilities. The Manager shall have the power and authority to disconnect the Project of a Project Company from the Shared Facilities (a) pursuant to Sections 9.3 or 9.5 upon liquidation and removal of the Shared Facilities, (b) as provided in Article 10 upon certain defaults hereunder, (c) if necessary, consistent with Good Utility Practice for the Operation and Maintenance of any portion of the Shared Facilities, or (d) if the Manager determines, in its good faith discretion, that disconnection is necessary in the event of an Emergency or to otherwise prevent damage or injury to persons or property, including to the other Projects, the Shared Facilities, the Interconnection Facilities or the property of the Participating Transmission Owner or as otherwise needed to prevent or mitigate technical issues affecting the Shared Facilities, provided that the Manager will use commercially reasonable efforts to give the Project Companies as much advance notice as is reasonably possible under the circumstances, consistent with responding to the Emergency or preventing damage or injury to persons or property, or (e) at the direction of the Participating Transmission Owner or the CAISO pursuant to rights under the Interconnection Agreement.
