Unless the Manager has in its good faith determined that it is unable to do so because an imminent threat of injury or death to persons, or damage to property exists, the Manager shall provide notice to the relevant Project Companies prior to or concurrently with disconnecting its Project from the Shared Facilities or as soon thereafter as is reasonably practical. In the event the Manager determines that any such disconnection is necessary, the Project Companies shall provide to the Manager promptly upon request such Project operational and control data as the Manager may consider necessary to implement such disconnection. 5.7 Books and Records; Reporting Requirements. (a) Maintenance of Records. The Manager shall maintain books and records related to the Shared Premises Property Rights and the Shared Facilities in sufficient detail to verify amounts incurred by the Manager and/or due and payable hereunder for a period of not less than three (3) years after the end of the calendar month to which they relate or such longer period as may be required by applicable law, and all such books and records shall be available for inspection and/or copying by each Party or its authorized representative at the cost and expense of such Party and at reasonable times during regular business hours, upon reasonable notice to the Manager. The costs incurred by the Manager in performing its obligations pursuant to this Section 5.7(a) shall be Shared O&M Expenses and shall be automatically added to the then current Approved Shared Facilities O&M Budget if not already included. (b) Provision of Records. The Manager shall, from time to time and at least once every calendar year, provide written reports to the Project Companies sufficient to keep the Project Companies reasonably apprised as to significant matters concerning the maintenance and repair of the Shared Premises and Shared Facilities, including such matters related thereto as may have a material impact on the operation, maintenance, and repair of each Project Company's Project. The costs incurred by the Manager in performing its obligations pursuant to this Section 5.7(b) shall be Shared O&M Expenses and shall be automatically added to the then current Approved Shared Facilities O&M Budget if not already included. (c) Audits. Each Project Company shall have the right to audit and make copies of the Manager's books and records for the Shared Facilities and the Shared Premises Property Rights, including with respect to construction costs for the Shared Facilities and Shared O&M Expenses, during normal business hours and upon reasonable advance notice to the Manager; provided that the Project Company requesting such audit shall be responsible for all costs associated with such audit, including reimbursing the Manager for any costs incurred by the Manager in responding to such request and in the performance of such audit. ARTICLE 6 MANAGER 6.1 Indemnification of the Manager. Each Project Company, severally on a pro rata basis based on its Proportionate Share, shall defend, indemnify and hold harmless the Manager and its shareholders, partners, principals, Affiliates (but not, for purposes of this Section 6.1, any Affiliate that is a Party), officers, directors, employees, agents and representatives, from any claim, loss, liability or damage incurred by reason of any act performed or omitted to be performed by it in good faith in performing its obligations under this Agreement, including without limitation, the management of the Shared Premises Property Rights, construction and Operation and Maintenance of the Shared Facilities (other than acts or omissions constituting gross negligence, fraud or willful misconduct by the Manager), including reasonable attorneys' fees incurred by it in connection with the defense of any action based on any such alleged act or omission. The Manager shall specifically be indemnified by the Project Companies and held harmless from any and all actions taken by the Manager in its reasonable judgment, in good faith, or in reasonable reliance on advice of the Manager's attorneys or accountants, and shall be reimbursed by the Project Companies for costs related to claims or litigation which arise in connection with the Shared Premises, the Shared Premises Property Rights, the Shared Facilities, or this Agreement (other than claims or litigation resulting from the Manager's gross negligence, fraud or willful misconduct). 6.2 Liability. Subject to Section 6.4, Manager shall not be liable, responsible or accountable in damages or otherwise to any Project Company or Secured Party for any act performed in good faith by the Manager in the discharge of its duties hereunder as the Manager or in the exercise of its powers and authority hereunder as the Manager, including damages arising out of the disconnection of, or the election not to disconnect, a Project Company's Project from the Shared Facilities, unless such acts or omissions constitute gross negligence, fraud or willful misconduct by the Manager, but such limitation does not limit the right of the Project Companies to declare a Manager Event of Default or remove the Manager for cause. 6.3 Limitation of Liability. In no event shall the liability of the Manager under this Agreement (other than liability arising out of gross negligence, fraud or willful misconduct) exceed, in any calendar year during the term hereof, the amount of actual insurance recoveries. IN NO EVENT, WHETHER BASED ON CONTRACT, INDEMNITY, WARRANTY, TORT (INCLUDING NEGLIGENCE) OR OTHERWISE, SHALL THE MANAGER OR ITS RESPECTIVE SUBCONTRACTORS AND SUPPLIERS BE LIABLE FOR SPECIAL, INCIDENTAL, EXEMPLARY, INDIRECT OR CONSEQUENTIAL DAMAGES, INCLUDING WITHOUT LIMITATION LOSS OF PROFITS OR REVENUE, COST OF CAPITAL, COST OF PURCHASED POWER, OR CLAIMS OF CUSTOMERS OF ANY PROJECT COMPANY FOR SUCH DAMAGES; provided, however, this Section 6.3 shall not be construed as a limitation or restriction on the amount or applicability of any insurance policies or coverages held by or otherwise required to be procured and obtained by the Parties under the terms of this Agreement. 6.4 Indemnification by the Manager. The Manager shall defend, indemnify and hold harmless each Project Company and each of their respective employees and agents, from any claim, loss, liability or damage incurred by reason of any gross negligence, fraud or willful misconduct by the Manager in the performance of its obligations under this Agreement, other than any claim, loss, liability or damage arising due to the gross negligence, fraud, willful misconduct or breach of this Agreement by a Project Company, including reasonable attorneys' fees incurred by it in connection with the defense of any action based thereon. 6.5 Removal of the Manager. The Manager may be removed, as set forth in this Section 6.5. (a) Removal for Cause. The Manager may be removed for cause by a Majority in Interest of the Project Companies, provided that each of the following conditions is satisfied: (1) A Manager Event of Default has occurred and is continuing. (2) The Project Company or Project Companies seeking removal of the Manager for cause have provided written notice (the "Removal Notice") to the Manager and the other Project Companies of the Manager Event of Default hereunder. Such notice shall contain a reasonably detailed description of the facts and circumstances giving rise to the default and identify a proposed replacement Manager. (3) All necessary consents under the Interconnection Agreement have been obtained. (4) Any dispute regarding the Manager Event of Default has been resolved and the dispute resolution has concluded that there is a Manager Event of Default. (b) Disputes. If any Project Company delivers a Removal Notice pursuant to Section 6.5(a) and the Manager disputes such default, then the following procedures shall apply: (1) Within five (5) Business Days after delivery of the Removal Notice, the Manager shall deliver to the Project Companies a notice with a detailed description of the reasons the Manager disputes such default, and within five (5) Business Days after delivery of such notice by the Manager, the Project Companies and the Manager shall meet and confer in good faith with respect to such default and the cure for such default. Such meeting and conference may be done either by telephone or in person. (2) If, after such meeting and conference, the Manager and the Project Companies cannot agree on whether a default exists, then any Party may submit such dispute to dispute resolution under Article 13. (c) Removal Without Cause. Subject to receipt of all necessary consents under the Interconnection Agreement, Manager may be removed without cause by agreement of all of the Project Companies upon sixty (60) days' prior written notice. (d) Successor Manager. No removal of the Manager shall be effective unless and until a successor Manager is appointed unless otherwise agreed by all of the Project Companies. Any Manager which is removed shall, in good faith, continue to undertake its duties and obligations as the Manager until such time as a successor Manager is appointed hereunder. In addition, the incumbent Manager shall cooperate with and assist the new Manager during any such transition period, including execution of all necessary documents and provision of all information and documentation that the new Manager may reasonably require to undertake its duties and obligations hereunder. If a Majority in Interest of the Project Companies fails to agree upon a replacement Manager within sixty (60) days after the decision to remove the Manager, the Project Companies will submit such dispute for resolution pursuant to the dispute resolution procedures set forth in Article 13. 6.6 Resignation. The Manager shall have the right to resign as the Manager upon sixty (60) days written notice to the Project Companies; provided, however, that the Manager may not resign unless all necessary consents under the Interconnection Agreement have been obtained. The Manager shall cooperate with the Project Companies in the transfer of the performance of the Manager's obligations to the Project Companies or a third party designated by Project Companies by the end of such sixty (60) day period, but the Manager's resignation shall not be effective until a replacement Manager is appointed. 6.7 Liability. The Manager will be discharged and released from all liability of the Manager accruing or arising under this Agreement on and after the date on which the Manager ceases to serve as Manager; provided, however, that no removal or resignation of the Manager will relieve the Manager of any liability accruing or arising prior to the date on which the Manager ceases to serve as Manager. 6.8 Delegation to Third Parties. The Manager may engage third parties and subcontractors (including the Manager's Affiliates) as it deems advisable for the purpose of performing or carrying out any of its obligations under this Agreement; provided, however, that no such engagement shall relieve the Manager of any of its obligations or liabilities under this Agreement, ARTICLE 7 INSURANCE 7.1 Property Insurance. Unless the Parties otherwise agree and subject in any event to Sections 7.9 and 7.10 below, the Manager shall arrange for "all risk" property insurance during operations for the Shared Facilities and the cost thereof shall be shared by the Project Companies in accordance with their respective Proportionate Shares; provided that each Party, at its discretion, may insure for its own business interruption losses. The "all risk" property insurance shall be in an amount sufficient to rebuild and replace the Shared Facilities in the event of a property damage loss thereof or damage thereto, including applicable sublimits. The Parties shall, and shall use commercially reasonable efforts to cause their Secured Parties to, cooperate and endorse all loss proceeds checks or waive their requirement to be a loss payee and take all reasonable actions to ensure loss proceeds are processed promptly and in accordance with the intent of this Agreement. Any property insurance procured by the Manager shall be primary as to any other insurance of the Parties and such policy shall waive the right of subrogation against the Parties. Any property insurance procured by a Project Company in lieu of insurance procured and maintained by the Manager pursuant to this Section 7.1 shall be primary as to any other insurance of the Parties and such policy shall waive the right of subrogation against the Parties. 7.2 Builder's All-Risk Insurance/All Risk Property Insurance. Any Party constructing or installing any Shared Facilities or Additional Facilities shall, during such construction or installation, maintain or cause to be maintained builder's all-risk insurance in an amount sufficient to replace any part of the Shared Facilities or Additional Facilities that may be affected by the construction. Such policies shall name each of the Parties and their Secured Parties as additional insureds and, to the extent obtainable on commercially reasonable terms, shall provide for thirty (30) days (ten (10) days in the case of non-payment of premiums) prior written notice before cancellation or modification. Once operational, all risk property insurance consistent with industry standards shall be procured to the extent available on commercially reasonable terms. 7.3 Liability Insurance. The Manager shall maintain liability insurance, including general liability coverage, covering the Shared Premises and the Shared Facilities, and each Project Company shall maintain liability insurance covering its Project and Property for any activities on the site of its Project or the Shared Premises. Each Party shall obtain and maintain comprehensive general liability insurance covering liability for bodily injury and death, property damage to third parties and damage to property of third parties in the care, custody and control of any Party and/or their respective employees in connection with operations at such Party's Project and the Shared Facilities. Such coverage shall have a minimum limit of not less than Twenty-One Million Dollars ($21,000,000) per occurrence and Twenty-One Million Dollars ($21,000,000) annual aggregate for bodily injury and property damage, provided that such coverage (i) may be provided as part of a blanket policy covering other properties and may be provided by a combination of primary and excess policies, (ii) may be provided through a combination of primary and excess (umbrella) liability insurance policies; (iii) shall comply with any statutory obligation imposed by workers compensation or occupational disease laws, (iv) shall contain a blanket broad form contractual endorsement and severability of interest clause, and (v) shall designate the Parties, the Secured Parties, and their officers, directors, employees and agents as additional insureds. If a policy described above is on a "claims made" basis, the retroactive date of the policy shall be the Agreement Date. Furthermore, if a policy is on a "claims made" basis, such coverage shall survive the termination of this Agreement until the expiration of the maximum statutory period of limitations in the State of California for actions based on contract or in tort. If coverage is on an "occurrence" basis, insurance on an occurrence basis shall be maintained for the term of this Agreement. 7.4 Workers Compensation. The Parties shall each obtain and maintain minimum coverage to comply with any statutory obligation imposed by workers compensation or occupational disease laws to the extent the Party uses its employees to perform duties under this Agreement. In the event the Party retains a subcontractor to perform any of such duties, it shall require such Person to comply with the requirements of this Section 7.4. 7.5 Automobile Liability. The Parties shall each also obtain and maintain an automobile liability insurance in the amounts they maintain for their other operations covering bodily injury and property damage, for hired, owned (if any) and non-owned vehicles to the extent their operations under this Agreement contemplate use of hired, owned and non-owned vehicles. 7.6 Casualty Event. In the event of a casualty that affects any of the Shared Facilities, all insurance proceeds with respect to the Shared Facilities shall be applied to reconstruction of the affected Shared Facilities. If there is uninsured loss or insurance proceeds are inadequate, the Parties shall contribute additional amounts based on their Proportionate Shares in the Shared Facilities; provided that additional amounts due with respect to any claims arising from the gross negligence or willful misconduct of a Party shall be first fully allocated to the account of such Party and then any balance not arising from the gross negligence or willful misconduct of such Party being contributed by the Parties based on their Proportionate Shares. In the event of any liability claim relating to any of the Shared Premises or Shared Facilities, to the extent such claim is not covered by the insurance required pursuant to this Article 7, the Parties shall be responsible for such claim based on their Proportionate Shares in the Shared Facilities; provided that additional amounts due with respect to any claims arising from the gross negligence or willful misconduct of a Party shall be first fully allocated to the account of such Party and then any balance not arising from the gross negligence or willful misconduct of such Party being contributed by the Parties based on their Proportionate Shares in the Shared Facilities. 7.7 Form and Content of Insurance. All policies and binders with respect to insurance provided pursuant to this Article 7 shall be as follows: (a) Form of Policies. All insurance provided for hereunder shall be placed on forms reasonably acceptable to the Parties and the Secured Parties. (b) Insurance Companies. All insurance required hereunder shall be with insurers with an A.M. Best rating of A minus or better or with insurers otherwise deemed acceptable to the Parties, and the Secured Parties. (c) Severability. All liability insurance shall contain a severability of interest provision providing that, except with respect to the total limits of liability, the insurance shall apply to each insured or additional insured in the same manner as if separate policies had been issued to each. (d) Non-Recourse. All insurance shall provide that there will be no recourse against the additional insureds for the payment of premiums or commissions or (if such policies provide for the payment thereof) additional premiums or assessments. 7.8 Additional Requirements. (a) Waiver of Subrogation. To the extent allowed by law, all insurance maintained by the Parties shall provide for the waiver of any right of subrogation by the insurers thereunder against the Parties and their Secured Parties and their officers, directors, employees, agents and representatives, and any right of the insurers to any setoff or counterclaim or any other deduction, whether by attachment or otherwise, in respect of any liability of any such person insured under such policy. (b) Non-Vitiation. To the extent obtainable on commercially reasonable terms, all property insurance maintained by the Parties shall provide for the waiver of any right of the insurers to terminate, repudiate, rescind or avoid this insurance as against any insured or any agent of any insured on the grounds that the risk or claim was not adequately disclosed, or that it was in any way misrepresented, or increased, or that any term, condition or warranty was breached, or on the ground of negligence, unless deliberate or fraudulent non-disclosure or misrepresentation or breach by that insured is established in relation thereto. (c) Notice of Cancellation. To the extent obtainable on commercially reasonable terms, all insurance shall provide that it may not be canceled or materially changed without at least thirty (30) days prior written notification thereof, except in cases of non-payment of premium for which ten (10) days prior written notice shall be provided. (d) Certificates; Proof of Loss. Prior to any construction activities on the site of a Project or the Shared Premises by a Party, such Party shall furnish certificates of insurance to the other Parties evidencing the insurance required of such Party pursuant to this Agreement. The Party maintaining each policy hereunder shall make all proofs of loss under each such policy, and shall take all other action reasonably required to ensure collection from insurers for any loss under any such policy, except that the other Party shall cooperate and assist in the preparation of such proofs of loss and take such other actions on behalf of the Parties as may be requested by the Parties. (e) Payment of Deductibles and Self-Insured Retention Amounts. Each Project Company shall be responsible for deductibles or self-insured retention under such Project Company's insurance policies. Any deductibles or self-insured retentions under policies obtained by the Manager pursuant to this Agreement shall be paid by the Project Companies as a Shared O&M Expense. (f) Subcontractor Insurance. Any Party performing work on the Shared Premises or the Shared Facilities shall require all contractors and subcontractors to carry commercial general liability insurance, automobile liability insurance and employer's liability insurance in the amount of at least One Million Dollars ($1,000,000) each and workers compensation insurance as required by law, and shall furnish the Manager with certificates of such insurance, prior to entry on the Shared Premises and during the time in which they are engaged in performing any services. (g) Notification. Each Party agrees to advise the other Parties as soon as practicable in writing of any notice of claim in excess of Two Hundred Fifty Thousand Dollars ($250,000) to which insurance pursuant to this Article 7 applies. (h) Failure To Procure. Should the Manager fail to provide or maintain any of the insurance policies required of it with respect to the Shared Premises or Shared Facilities, the Project Companies shall have the right to provide and/or maintain such coverage at after a reasonable time to cure has passed. Any cost incurred by a Project Company in so doing shall be reimbursed to such Project Company, and payed by all of the Project Companies as a Shared O&M Expense. (i) Allocation of Costs. All premiums for insurance obtained by the Manager shall be considered Shared O&M Expenses for purposes of this Agreement. 7.9 Limitation on Insurance Requirements. (a) Notwithstanding anything in this Article 7 to the contrary, if insurance meeting the requirements set forth herein is not available on commercially reasonable terms, then the Manager shall obtain such insurance on terms in accordance with the requirements of this Article 7 to the extent, if any, such insurance is available on commercially reasonably terms, as certified by the Manager to the Parties. Any Project Company shall have the right, at its sole cost and expense, to obtain insurance with respect to such Project Company's Proportionate Share for its own account and/or for the benefit of its Secured Party to the extent the Manager cannot obtain such insurance. (b) Insurance obtained by the Manager or a Project Company pursuant to the Interconnection Agreement, Co-Tenancy Agreement, or any Power Purchase Agreement may, if it meets the minimum requirement of this Article 7 satisfy a Party's insurance obligations under this Agreement. 7.10 Right to Self-Insure. Notwithstanding anything in this Article 7 to the contrary, unless otherwise prohibited by the Interconnection Agreement, Co-Tenancy Agreement or a Power Purchase Agreement of a Project Company, the Manager shall have the option to self-insure for the insurance it is required to obtain and maintain hereunder on such terms and conditions as all of the Parties may mutually agree. ARTICLE 8 ASSIGNMENTS AND RIGHT TO ENCUMBER 8.1 Assignment by Parties. No Party shall assign, sell, dispose of, give or otherwise transfer (collectively "assign" or "assignment") its rights and interests under this Agreement, to any person, except with the consent of the other Parties or as provided in Section 4.7, Section 8.3 or Section 9.2. If the procedures provided in Section 8.2 are complied with, the assigning Party shall be released from any further obligations hereunder arising from and after the effective date of such assignment (to the extent of the interest assigned), and such assignee shall become a Party under this Agreement. Notwithstanding the foregoing, (a) the sale or other transfer of ownership interests in any Project Company (or any of its constituent members, partners or upstream parents) in connection with any sale, merger, reorganization, foreclosure or tax equity financing that does not involve an assignment of this Agreement, (b) any assignment by a Project Company of its rights under this Agreement to the entity into which or with which such Project Company may be merged or consolidated, or (c) any assignment by a Project Company of all of its rights under this Agreement to any Qualified Transferee to which such Project Company transfers all or substantially all of its Project, shall each be expressly permitted hereunder without the consent of the other Parties; provided that any such assignee, transferee or successor entity shall comply with the requirements of Section 8.2. Any attempted assignment of any interest in the Shared Facilities or this Agreement made other than in accordance with this Section 8.1, either voluntarily or by operation of law, will be void and of no force or effect whatsoever. 8.2 Procedures. No Party shall be bound by any assignment, no assignment shall be valid, and no assignee of any Party's rights under this Agreement shall become a Party unless (i) all Parties consent to the assignment to the extent required by Section 8.1; (ii) the assignee will own and operate the Project of the assigning Party; (iii) the assignee promptly cures any outstanding breaches or defaults of the assigning Party that are capable of being cured, (iv) the assignee agrees in writing, in form and substance reasonably satisfactory to the other Parties, to assume all of the present and future obligations of the assigning Party under this Agreement and to be bound by the terms of this Agreement in the place and stead of the assigning Party, to the extent of the interest assigned, and (v) a counterpart of the instrument of assignment, executed by the parties thereto, is delivered to the other Parties. 8.3 Right to Encumber. (a) Amendment of Agreement in Connection with Project Company Financing. The Parties acknowledge that a Project Company may finance all or part of its costs in connection with the transactions contemplated by this Agreement. In the event that a Project Company does enter into such financing, the Parties acknowledge and agree that certain aspects of the transactions contemplated hereby may need to be modified in certain respects to accommodate the reasonable requirements of any lender with respect to such financing. The Parties hereby agree to cooperate in good faith and to use commercially reasonable efforts to assist a Project Company to make or to obtain any modification of this Agreement or the transactions contemplated hereby reasonably requested by a Project Company to allow the Project Company to obtain such financing upon commercially reasonable terms, including obtaining consents to the assignment for security purposes of a Project Company's Proportionate Share interest in the Shared Facilities reasonably requested by such Project Company's lender, provided that the Parties will not be required to cooperate with a Project Company to implement any modification which would (i) relieve such Project Company of any of its obligations under this Agreement or the transactions contemplated hereby, (ii) decrease the economic benefits or increase the costs of the transactions contemplated hereby to any of the other Parties, or (iii) create any additional economic or legal risks to any of the other Parties or any of their respective Affiliates. The Project Company seeking the financing will be responsible for the reasonable attorney's fees and other out-of-pocket costs incurred by the other Parties in providing such cooperation and efforts under this Section 8.3. (b) Right to Encumber. So long as such actions do not violate, result in breach of, or cause the loss or termination of the Interconnection Agreement, Co-Tenancy Agreement, any Shared Premise Property Right, or a Power Purchase Agreement each Party specifically agrees that (i) any Project Company may at any time pledge, collaterally assign, encumber, or grant a security interest in the entirety of its rights under this Agreement to any Secured Party concurrently with pledging, collaterally assigning, encumbering or granting a security interest in such Project Company's Project to such Secured Party and (ii) it will execute such consents to collateral assignment as may be reasonably requested by a Project Company or that Project Company's Secured Parties confirming, among other things, (A) the Project Company's right to the Shared Facilities Services, (B) that there are no known Project Company defaults under this Agreement, and (iii) the Shared Facilities capital costs paid to date. (c) Pledge, Collateral Assignment or Encumbrance. Should a Project Company pledge, collaterally assign or encumber its rights under this Agreement as provided in Section 8.3(b) above, the Parties hereto expressly agree between themselves and for the benefit of any Secured Party that (i) no Party shall amend this Agreement in any material respect unless the consent of all the Secured Parties is first obtained, (ii) upon the occurrence of a default by a Project Company hereunder, the non-defaulting Party declaring the default shall also provide written notice to the defaulting Party's Secured Parties of such default (and accept their cure of such default on the terms set forth herein), (iii) each such Secured Party shall have the same period after receipt of a notice of default to cure, or cause to be cured, the default described therein, as is given to the defaulting Party, plus, in each instance, any additional cure periods provided under the Security Documents, not to exceed (a) thirty (30) days in the event of any monetary default; Such new Shared Facilities agreement shall be effective as of the date of the termination of this Agreement by reason of default by the Insolvent Party or upon the date of rejection of this Agreement by the Insolvent Party in its bankruptcy proceeding, on the same terms, covenants, conditions and agreements as contained in this Agreement. Upon the acceptance of the Secured Party, or its designee or assignee, as a Party hereunder, or upon execution of any such new Shared Facilities agreement, the Secured Parties, or their designees or assignees, of the Insolvent Party shall (A) pay the Solvent Parties any unpaid amounts which are due the Solvent Parties from the Insolvent Party under the terms of this Agreement, and (B) promptly perform or cause to be performed all of the other covenants and agreements set forth in this Agreement to be performed by the Insolvent Party to the extent that the Insolvent Party failed to perform the same prior to the execution and delivery of the new Shared Facilities agreement. Notwithstanding anything in this Article 8 to the contrary, if FERC approval is required for a transfer of a Party's interest hereunder, no Party may transfer its interests in this Agreement, and no purported transfer will be effective, unless and until such Party has obtained all necessary approvals from the FERC to effectuate any changes in this Agreement to reflect such transfer and the changes in the Parties to this Agreement, to the extent required by FERC. 8.6 Further Assurances. In the event of an assignment or transfer in part by a Party pursuant to Section 8.1 above, the Parties shall, at the reasonable request and expense of the assigning Party, execute and deliver a separate agreement with such assignee together with any necessary amendment to this Agreement, such that this Agreement, as amended, and such separate agreement shall cumulatively allocate the respective rights of the assigning Party and the assignee following such assignment; provided that in no event shall such amendment or separate agreement increase any obligation or liability of any of the other Parties or otherwise adversely impact such Parties rights in and to the Shared Premises and Shared Facilities under this Agreement, without the express consent of such Party thereto. ARTICLE 9 TERM AND TERMINATION 9.1 Term and Termination. The term of this Agreement shall commence as of the Agreement Date and shall terminate, subject to obtaining any necessary prior FERC approvals for such termination, upon the mutual agreement of all of the Parties, with the consent of the then-existing Secured Parties, if applicable. Upon such termination, the Parties shall execute and record a notice of such termination with a reference to the Memorandum, as it may have been amended. 9.2 Termination as to a Project Company: Surrender of Interests. Any Project Company may elect to surrender all of its interests hereunder and in and to the Shared Premises, the Shared Premises Property Rights and the Shared Facilities and to assign its rights hereunder to the other Project Companies, but only with the consent of all of the other Project Companies, and, thereupon, to cease to have any right, title or interest in this Agreement, the Shared Premises, Shared Premises Property Rights, and Shared Facilities; provided that (A) the Surrendering Party executes and delivers all instruments of transfer as may be necessary or appropriate to effect (and that do effect) the assignment of such rights to the other Project Companies, in form and substance reasonably acceptable to the other Project Companies, (B) the Surrendering Party is not then in default of its obligations under this Agreement or the other Project Companies to which such rights are being assigned have agreed in writing to promptly cure such defaults, and (C) each Secured Party that holds a security interest in such rights has consented in writing to such surrender and assignment and has released or agreed to release such Secured Party's security interest in the interests being assigned and in the Shared Premises, the Shared Premises Property Rights and the Shared Facilities. The Surrendering Party shall remain fully responsible for, and shall pay (i) its applicable Proportionate Share of all Shared O&M Expenses and other obligations and liabilities hereunder through the effective date of its surrender and assignment, and (ii) its applicable Proportionate Share of the Shared Facilities Construction Costs (including in respect of any Additional Facilities that have been added prior to such surrender and assignment). In addition, the Surrendering Party shall be responsible for obtaining any FERC approval required for the transfer and all costs associated with obtaining such rights. 9.3 Abandonment or Decommissioning of a Project. In addition to the obligations set forth in Section 7 and Section 9.2, in the event a Surrendering Party desires to decommission and/or abandon its Project, the Surrendering Party shall, upon notice to the other Parties of its intent to decommission and/or abandon its Project, be responsible for the removal of any Shared Facilities no longer required by the remaining Parties due to the decommissioning and/or abandonment of the Surrendering Party's Project, and upon the failure of the Surrendering Party to remove or release same, the Manager may remove or release same on behalf of such Surrendering Party and shall charge the Surrendering Party all costs incurred to accomplish such removal or release, plus ten percent (10%) of such costs for the services of the Manager in procuring and supervising such work. In addition, the Surrendering Party shall be responsible for and shall pay its Proportionate Share of all Shared O&M Expenses and other obligations and liabilities hereunder through the effective date of abandonment; the Surrendering Party shall further remain fully responsible for, and shall pay (i) its applicable Proportionate Share of all Shared O&M Expenses and other obligations and liabilities hereunder through the effective date of its surrender and assignment, and (ii) its applicable Proportionate Share of the Shared Facilities Construction Costs (including in respect of any Additional Facilities that have been added prior to such surrender and assignment). 9.4 Cooperation Upon Surrender, Abandonment and/or Decommissioning of a Project. The Parties recognize that some of the Shared Premises Property Rights may exist because of the existing rights of a Project Company pursuant to a separate agreement between that Project Company and a third party. If, after receiving notice from a Surrendering Party that it intends to surrender its interests or intends to abandon or decommission its Project, the remaining Project Companies will review the Shared Premises Property Rights to determine whether such surrender, abandonment or decommissioning will cause the termination or expiration of any necessary Shared Premises Property Rights. If the remaining Project Companies reasonably determine that, by virtue of the Surrendering Party's surrender of its interests and/or abandonment or decommissioning, necessary Shared Premises Property Rights may be terminated or may expire, the Surrendering Party shall use commercially reasonable efforts to cooperate with the remaining Project Companies and the Manager to obtain replacement agreements so that the Project Companies have all rights necessary for this Agreement to remain in full force and effect so that the remaining Project Companies continue to enjoy the full benefits of this Agreement pursuant to the purposes stated herein, and the Surrendering Party may not surrender, abandon and/or decommission such Project until such Shared Premises Property Rights have been secured for the other Project Companies. 9.5 Distribution on Termination of this Agreement. In the event that the Project Companies decide to decommission all of the Projects and to proceed with the removal of the Shared Facilities, the Manager shall take account of the Shared Premises, Shared Premises Property Rights and Shared Facilities, and any other assets or liabilities related thereto, and after obtaining any necessary FERC approvals, shall proceed with the liquidation thereof. The assets shall be liquidated under the supervision of the Manager as promptly as is consistent with obtaining a reasonable value therefor, and the proceeds therefrom, together with any assets distributed in-kind, shall be applied and distributed as follows: 9.5.1 To the payment of debts and liabilities of the Parties to third parties in connection with the Shared Facilities which are then due and the expenses of liquidation (including expenses incurred by the Manager) on a pro-rata and pari passu basis, based upon each Project Company's Proportionate Share in the Shared Facilities as of the date of liquidation. 9.5.2 To the setting up of any reserves which the Manager deems reasonably necessary for any contingent or unforeseen liabilities or obligations or debts not yet payable by the Parties in connection with Shared Premises, Shared Premises Property Rights and the Shared Facilities, including any reserves to pay costs associated with the decommissioning and removal of the Shared Facilities, provided that any Party may elect to Dispute, and to submit to arbitration, the amount determined by the Manager for any such reserves pursuant to Section 13.2 below. 9.5.3 Any sum remaining shall be distributed on a pro-rata basis to the Project Companies, based upon each Project Company's Proportionate Share as of the date of final termination of this Agreement. 9.5.4 The Manager shall thereupon have the right, to disconnect the Shared Facilities from the Interconnection Facilities and the Projects, subject to obtaining any FERC approvals necessary for such actions. 9.6 Valuation and Distribution of Non-Cash Distributions. To the extent that non-cash consideration is distributed in kind as permitted herein, the fair market value of such assets shall first be determined by an independent valuation expert selected by the Parties, including separate valuations for each of Shared Premises, Shared Premises Property Rights and the Shared Facilities, and the distribution of assets shall be made in accordance with such valuation. ARTICLE 10 DEFAULT AND REMEDIES 10.1 Project Company Default. A Project Company shall be in default under this Agreement if such Project Company (each of the following constituting a "Project Company Event of Default"): (a) Fails to pay when due any amounts required to be paid by such Project Company under the terms of this Agreement and such failure to pay is not cured within fifteen (15) days following written notice from the Manager or another Party to whom such amount is owed specifying the amount to be paid; (b) Except as provided in Sections 4.4 and 9.4, permits a separate agreement to which it is a party to expire prior to the expiration or earlier termination of this Agreement, and the expiration of such agreement would jeopardize the validity or enforceability of any Shared Premises Property Right; (c) Breaches, or causes the breach of a Shared Premises Property Right and fails to cure such breach within the time permitted by such Shared Premises Property Right, after receipt of a notice of default from the Manager to cure, or cause to be cured, the default described therein, as is given to the defaulting Party less, in each instance, the following reduced time periods: (i) five (5) days less than the specified cure period under the Shared Premises Property Right in the event of any monetary default; and (ii) ten (10) days less than the specified cure period under the Shared Premises Property Right in the event of any non-monetary default. Each of the Parties agrees to provide a copy of any notice of default under a Shared Premises Property Right that is received by such Party to the other Parties and their Secured Parties under this Agreement within forty-eight (48) hours of receiving such notice of default or breach, regardless of the Party or the contract that is alleged in the notice to be in default or to have breached; (d) Breaches or causes the breach of the Interconnection Agreement or the Co-Tenancy Agreement, and such defaulting Project Company fails to cure such breach by the time that is ten (10) days less than the specified cure period under the Interconnection Agreement or Co-Tenancy Agreement, as applicable, provided that in no event shall the resulting cure period available to the Project Company be less than five (5) Business Days. Each of the Parties agrees to provide a copy of any notice of default received by them to the other Parties and their Secured Parties under this Agreement within forty-eight (48) hours of receiving such notice of default, regardless of the party or the contract that is alleged to be in default in the notice; (e) Breaches or causes the breach of any Conditional Use Permit, and such defaulting Project Company fails to cure such breach within the earlier of (i) lapse of the applicable cure period in the Conditional Use Permit and (ii) ten (10) days following the Project Company's receipt of written notice of the breach in accordance with the terms of the Conditional Use Permit, provided that if the breach is not reasonably capable of being cured within ten (10) days and the applicable cure period in the Conditional Use Permit has not lapsed and there is no material adverse effect on any Project, then the breach shall be deemed cured if the defaulting Project Company commences, diligently pursues, and completes action that remedies the default within thirty (30) days of receipt of such notice, or if a shorter period applies under the Conditional Use Permit, within such shorter period. Each of the Parties agrees to provide a copy of any notice of default under any Conditional Use Permit received by them to the other Parties and their Secured Parties under this Agreement within forty-eight (48) hours of receiving such notice of default, regardless of the party or the contract that is alleged to be in default in the notice; (f) Fails to cure any other failure to perform any obligation under this Agreement not covered in the preceding clauses (a) through (e) within thirty (30) days following written notice from any other Party specifying the nature of the failure to perform, provided that if the default is not reasonably capable of being cured within thirty (30) days, then the default shall be deemed cured if the defaulting Project Company commences, diligently pursues, and completes action that remedies the default within ninety (90) days of receipt of such notice; or (g) Makes an assignment for the benefit of creditors, files a petition in bankruptcy, voluntarily takes advantage of any bankruptcy or insolvency laws or is otherwise adjudicated bankrupt or judicially insolvent, in each case, immediately upon such occurrence or, if a petition or an answer is filed proposing the adjudication of such Project Company as bankrupt, when such Project Company shall consent to the filing thereof or sixty (60) days after the filing thereof unless the same shall have been discharged, opposed, or denied prior thereto. A copy of any notice of a Project Company default or Project Company Event of Default shall be provided, to the extent required pursuant to this Section 10.1, to any Secured Party in accordance with Section 8.3(c), and the non-defaulting Parties shall accept curative performance from any such Secured Party in accordance with Section 8.3(c). Notwithstanding anything to the contrary in this Section 10.1, a non-defaulting Party shall not be required to provide notice to a Secured Party unless the defaulting Project Company has, prior to the occurrence of the relevant underlying default, provided each of the Manager and the other Project Companies written notice of the name of such Secured Party and a contact person, address, telephone, facsimile number and email address for a single representative or agent of the Secured Parties of such defaulting Project Company designated to receive such notices. 10.2 Manager Event of Default. The Manager shall be in default under this Agreement if the Manager (each of the following constituting a "Manager Event of Default"): (a) Fails to pay when due any amounts required to be paid by the Manager under the terms of this Agreement and such failure to pay is not cured within fifteen (15) days following written notice from another Party to whom such amount is owed specifying the amount to be paid; (b) Makes an assignment for the benefit of creditors, files a petition in bankruptcy, voluntarily takes advantage of any bankruptcy or insolvency laws or is otherwise adjudicated bankrupt or judicially insolvent, in each case, immediately upon such occurrence or, if a petition or an answer is filed proposing the adjudication of the Manager as bankrupt, when the Manager shall consent to the filing thereof or sixty (60) days after the filing thereof unless the same shall have been discharged, opposed, or denied prior thereto; (c) Breaches, or causes the breach of the terms of a Shared Premises Property Right and fails to cure such breach within the time permitted by the terms of such Shared Premises Property Right, after receipt of a notice of default from a Party to cure, or cause to be cured, the default described therein, as is given to the Manager less, in each instance, the following reduced time periods: (i) five (5) days less than the specified cure period under the Shared Premises Property Right in the event of any monetary default; and (ii) ten (10) days less than the specified cure period under the terms of the Shared Premises Property Right in the event of any non-monetary default; (d) Fails to cure an "Owner Event of Default" under either the EPC Contract or the O&M Agreement within fifteen (15) days after its occurrence, in the case of an Owner Event of Default that can be cured by the payment of money, or forty-five (45) days after its occurrence, in the case of an Owner Event of Default that cannot be cured solely by the payment of money; or (e) Fails to perform any other material covenant or obligation under this Agreement not covered by the foregoing clauses (a) through (d) within thirty (30) days following written notice from any Party specifying the nature of the failure to perform, provided that if the default is not reasonably capable of being cured within thirty (30) days, Manager shall have such additional period, not to exceed an additional sixty (60) days, to cure such failure. 10.3 Remedies. (a) Default by a Project Company. Upon the occurrence and during the continuation of a Project Company Event of Default, the non-defaulting Parties shall have the following remedies: (1) Draw upon any financial security provided by the defaulting Party; (2) In their sole and absolute discretion, to cure the default of the defaulting Party by making or tendering the required payment or performance, and permitting the defaulting Party's Project to continue to have the use of the Shared Facilities Services, provided that any such amounts paid by the non-defaulting Parties, including all reasonable attorneys' fees and costs, shall be treated as a loan to the defaulting Party, which loan shall accrue interest until repaid in full at the Default Interest Rate; (3) To disconnect the defaulting Project Company's Project, provided, that (A) the Manager shall have in good faith determined that bringing an action for money damages and/or for specific performance will not provide an adequate or timely remedy for such default, and (B) the Majority in Interest of non-defaulting Project Companies shall have consented in writing to such disconnection; provided, further that the defaulting Project Company shall be permitted to reconnect promptly when and if the default is cured, any necessary approvals from the CAISO and/or the Participating Transmission Owner have been obtained, and in the case of any such reconnection, the non-defaulting Project Companies and the Manager shall have been compensated in full for any and all damage incurred by them as a result of such Project Company Event of Default; (4) To bring an action to specifically enforce the provisions of this Agreement; (5) To bring an action for money damages or other appropriate relief; or (6) To exercise any other rights and remedies which the non-defaulting Parties might have at law or in equity, other than termination of this Agreement. (b) Default by the Manager. Upon the occurrence and during the continuation of a Manager Event of Default, each Project Company shall have the following remedies: (1) To remove the Manager for cause pursuant to the procedures set forth in Section 6.5 of this Agreement; (2) To bring an action to specifically enforce the provisions of this Agreement; (3) In their sole and absolute discretion, to cure the default of the Manager by making or tendering the required payment or performance, provided that any such amounts paid by the Project Companies, including all reasonable attorneys' fees and costs, shall be treated as a loan to the Manager, which loan shall accrue interest until repaid in full at the Default Interest Rate; and (4) to exercise any and all other rights and remedies that any one or more of the Project Companies might otherwise have at law or in equity, other than the termination of this Agreement. (c) All of the foregoing remedies are cumulative and non-exclusive, and the exercise of any one remedy at any one time shall not constitute the waiver of any other remedy at a later or different time. In addition, the Parties agree that damages may not be an adequate remedy for a default under this Agreement, and that a non-defaulting Party will be entitled to seek specific performance, injunctive or other equitable relief against the defaulting Party in order to prevent or eliminate such default or to exercise the non-defaulting Party's remedies under this Agreement on account of such default. 10.4 Waiver of Right to Partition or Distribution. Each Party acknowledges and agrees that it would be prejudicial to the interests of the Parties under this Agreement if any Party were to seek partition or any other type of division of the Shared Premises Property Rights, the Shared Facilities or any other shared rights, assets or properties, or to file an action for such partition or division. Therefore, in consideration of such fact and for other good and valuable consideration, each of the Parties hereby waives and relinquishes any and all rights that it may have to seek a partition or any other type of division of any rights or interests in the Shared Premises Property Rights, the Shared Facilities or any other shared rights, assets or properties that are subject to this Agreement. In the event any dispute involves common issues of fact, liability or responsibility with any dispute or controversy under any other agreement (including any Power Purchase Agreement, the Interconnection Agreements, and other project agreements), each of the Parties agrees, where reasonably justified, may join such disputes and controversies to seek a common resolution of all such matters. 13.2.2 Technical Disputes. (a) Any Dispute which is mutually agreed by the Parties (each acting in its sole discretion) to involve engineering, construction or technical matters as the sole or primary area of disagreement between the Parties shall be deemed to be a "Technical Dispute" (each, a "Technical Dispute") and shall be resolved in accordance with the procedures specified in this Section 13.2.2. (b) Any Technical Dispute shall first be subject to the provisions of Section 13.1 above, and if the Technical Dispute is not resolved by the Parties pursuant thereto, any Party (the "Disputing Party") may refer the Technical Dispute for resolution by providing written notice delivered to the other Party or Parties (the "Opposing Party") (i) stating the general nature of the Technical Dispute, (ii) stating the amount or extent of such Technical Dispute and (iii) attaching supporting data for such Technical Dispute. (c) The Disputing Party and the Opposing Party, acting reasonably and in good faith, shall designate an independent technical expert with a minimum of ten (10) years of experience in the area that is the subject of the dispute to resolve the Technical Dispute (the "Technical Dispute Arbitrator"). Within five (5) Business Days following receipt of the Disputing Party's notice regarding a Technical Dispute, the Parties shall confer in an effort to agree upon a Technical Dispute Arbitrator. If the Parties are unable to agree upon the appointment of a Technical Dispute Arbitrator, then at the end of such five (5) Business Day period each Party shall, within three (3) Business Days, notify the other Party in writing of its designation of a proposed Technical Dispute Arbitrator. Within three (3) Business Days of each Party's receipt of the proposed Technical Dispute Arbitrator, the two proposed Technical Dispute Arbitrators shall select a qualified independent third party to be the Technical Dispute Arbitrator. (d) The Opposing Party shall submit any response to the Disputing Party and the Technical Dispute Arbitrator within twenty (20) Business Days after receipt of the Disputing Party's last submittal (unless the Technical Dispute Arbitrator allows additional time or the Parties otherwise agree), and the Disputing Party shall submit any reply thereto within ten (10) Business Days of receipt thereof (unless the Technical Dispute Arbitrator allows additional time or the Parties otherwise agree). Each Party's submission shall be in the form of written statements of position by such Party, and each Party shall have the opportunity to respond to the written statements of the other Party and to any requests for statements or information by the Technical Dispute Arbitrator; provided, however, that other than as provided in the immediately preceding sentence, all such submissions by a Party shall be made within three (3) Business Days of receipt of the submission or request to which it responds, and, notwithstanding any provision herein to the contrary, any unresolved disputed items shall be determined by the Technical Dispute Arbitrator within twenty (20) Business Days of receipt by the Technical Dispute Arbitrator of the Parties' latest submissions of information. Upon the request of all Parties, the Technical Dispute Arbitrator shall meet jointly with the Parties or their representatives with respect to any such Technical Dispute during such five (5) Business Day period. If the Technical Dispute Arbitrator does not render a formal decision in writing within the time stated in this Section 13.2.2(d), the Parties may initiate an arbitration as set forth in Section 13.2.1 to resolve the Dispute. (e) If the amount in controversy is equal to or greater than $500,000, the decision of the Technical Dispute Arbitrator shall not be final and binding. With respect to such Technical Disputes, if any Party is dissatisfied with the decision of the Technical Dispute Arbitrator, such Party may initiate arbitration proceedings as set forth in Section 13.2.1; provided, however, that the written decision of the Technical Dispute Arbitrator shall be admissible in evidence in any such arbitration. If the amount in controversy is less than $500,000, then the decision of the Technical Dispute Arbitrator shall be final and binding on the Parties. (f) Either Party (i) may provide reports and information prepared by a third party engineer or expert of its choice in connection with the written notice under Section 13.2.2(b), the submissions under Section 13.2.2(d), and in responding to any requests by the Technical Dispute Arbitrator, and (ii) may provide any such other evidence as it considers relevant provided that such evidence and the presentation thereof complies with any Arbitration Rules that relate to such matters. The Technical Dispute Arbitrator shall provide his or her decision in the form of a written, reasoned opinion. The Technical Dispute Arbitrator shall not be personally liable to any Party in connection with any interpretation or decision rendered in good faith in such capacity. All costs of the Technical Dispute Arbitrator shall be borne by the Party whose position in the Dispute is not supported by the decision of the Technical Dispute Arbitrator unless the decision of the Technical Dispute Arbitrator does not clearly support one Party's position, in which event such costs shall be borne by the Parties involved in such Dispute in their Proportionate Shares in the Shared Facilities. 13.2.3 Filing Deadlines. The Parties agree that arbitration pursuant to Sections 13.2.1 and 13.2.2 must be initiated within a reasonable time after the claim, dispute or other matter in question has arisen, and in no event shall it be made after the date when institution of legal or equitable proceedings based on such claim, dispute or other matter in question would be barred by the applicable statutes of limitations.
