ARTICLE II CO-TENANCY RIGHTS AND OBLIGATIONS 2.1 Declaration of Intention. The Parties hereby declare that their relationship in and to the LGIA and the Interconnection Customer's rights and obligations thereunder is and will be that of tenants-in-common, and that each Co-Tenant will have an undivided interest ("Undivided Interest") in the LGIA and the Interconnection Customer's rights and obligations thereunder, expressly subject, however, to the terms, conditions, limitations and requirements set forth in this Agreement. Nothing contained in this Agreement will be deemed to constitute the Parties as partners or joint venturers. The Parties acknowledge and agree that the Rojo Project, the Amarillo Project, the Azul Project, and the Verde Project will be treated as a single Project under the LGIA and that there can be no more than four co-tenants under the LGIA without the consent of CAISO and the Participating TO. 2.2 Use of LGIA. The LGIA shall be held and used solely to permit the interconnection of the Projects to the CAISO Controlled Grid and to deliver electricity and electricity-related products generated or otherwise made available by the respective Projects owned by each Co-Tenant (or by such Co-Tenant's successors or permitted assigns) at the Point of Interconnection. No Co-Tenant may use or permit the use of the LGIA in a manner that would reasonably be expected to interfere with the use and enjoyment by any other Co-Tenant of such Co-Tenant's Project, or to violate Applicable Laws and Regulations; provided that a Co-Tenant's use of the LGIA in compliance with this Agreement shall be deemed to not interfere with any other Co-Tenant's use and enjoyment of its Project. In the event of a conflict between the terms of the LGIA and this Agreement, the terms of the LGIA shall prevail. 2.3 Maximum Capacity. No Co-Tenant shall interconnect its respective Project to the Point of Interconnection to the extent the installed capacity of such Project exceeds its Maximum Capacity at the Point of Interconnection. To the extent that conditions exist which result in a Co-Tenant delivering energy to the Point of Interconnection from its respective Project in excess of the Maximum Capacity in respect of such Project, then such Co-Tenant shall at its expense immediately curtail the operation of its Project so as not to exceed its Maximum Capacity. 2.4 Curtailment. (a) The Manager may, in accordance with this Section 2.4, direct the Co-Tenants to interrupt or reduce deliveries of electrical power (i) with the prior consent of all of the Co-Tenants (not including any Defaulting Party), when necessary in order to maintain, repair, replace, remove, investigate, inspect or test any part of any Project; (ii) if the Manager determines, in its reasonable discretion, that interruption or reduction is necessary due to an Emergency Condition; or (iii) at the direction of the Participating TO or the CAISO pursuant to rights under the LGIA. Manager will use commercially reasonable efforts to give the Co-Tenants as much advance notice as is reasonably possible for interruptions, reductions or curtailments under this clause (a). (b) With respect to any interruption or reduction of deliveries of electrical power pursuant to clauses (i) or (ii) of Section 2.4(a), the Manager shall limit the length and quantity of any such interruption or curtailment to the minimum extent and minimum time strictly necessary to correct the problem. Any interruption or curtailment made pursuant to clause (i) of Section 2.4(a) shall be made consistent with Good Utility Practice and to the extent commercially reasonable during periods of low or no solar generation or low energy prices. (c) In the event of any curtailment of interconnection services at the direction of CAISO or Participating TO, subject to Section 2.4(d), such curtailment shall be allocated in the following manner until such curtailment is achieved: (i) first, each Co-Tenant (if any) that is delivering energy in excess of such Co-Tenant's Maximum Capacity shall reduce deliveries down to such Co-Tenant's Maximum Capacity; (ii) second, each Co-Tenant that is delivering test power shall reduce all such deliveries down to zero; (iii) third, as provided in and to the extent applicable under Sections 2.4(d)(ii) below, until all such curtailments have been applied or any or all Co-Tenants have been fully curtailed; and (iv) fourth, subject to Section 2.4(d)(i) below, to the extent it has not already been fully curtailed, each Co-Tenant shall reduce its energy deliveries so that they do not exceed an amount (the "Curtailed Output Cap") equal to (X) such Co-Tenant's Maximum Capacity, minus (Y) the product of (1) the aggregate number of MWs then required for the combined Projects to curtail (after application of preceding clause (i)) times (2) such Co-Tenant's Percentage Interest; provided, further, that if during any relevant period of curtailment any Co-Tenant is delivering energy at a level less than its Curtailed Output Cap (any such amount, a "Shortfall") either because such Co-Tenant's Project is undergoing maintenance, has a forced outage, or other circumstance, then for so long as such Shortfall exists, the Manager shall use reasonable efforts to authorize any other Co-Tenant to generate above such Co-Tenant's Curtailed Output Cap. (d) Notwithstanding the other provisions of this Section 2.4: (i) The Manager (with the prior consent of all of the Co-Tenants (not including any Defaulting Party), in the case of curtailments under Section 2.4(a)(i)) shall curtail on a non-pro rata, but equitable and reasonable basis (as determined by the Manager in good faith) if (A) in spite of the Manager's good faith efforts to direct the Co-Tenants to comply with this Section 2.4, curtailment of interconnection services directed by the CAISO or Participating TO is not otherwise achievable, or (B) such non-pro rata allocation is otherwise necessary to comply with the LGIA or CAISO or Participating TO direction, and, in each of the foregoing clauses (A) and (B), that such non-pro rata allocation will not result in a default under the LGIA; and (ii) To the extent that the need for any curtailment, interruption or reduction can be attributed to a particular Co-Tenant's Project or portions of its Project or the failure of such Project to comply with the order to curtail or a default by such Co-Tenant under the LGIA or an applicable power purchase agreement, or to the extent such Co-Tenant's Project is the cause of an Emergency Condition or is directed by CAISO or the Participating TO to curtail, then all such curtailment shall be allocated first to such Co-Tenant and such Co-Tenant will be responsible for all costs, liabilities, and damages resulting from such curtailment (subject to the limitations in this Agreement) and the Manager shall, to the extent possible, limit such interruption or reduction to such Project or such portions of the Project, as the case may be. (e) Each Co-Tenant shall promptly effect such interruption in, or reduction of, delivery as the Manager shall direct pursuant to this Section 2.4 (with the prior consent of all of the Co-Tenants (not including any Defaulting Party), in the case of curtailments under Section 2.4(a)(i)) upon notice from the Manager. In the event notice is impracticable or a Co-Tenant fails to promptly comply therewith, the Manager may effect the same by direct action. A Co-Tenant that fails to implement any such curtailment, interruption or reduction, shall be responsible for all cost and expenses related thereto, including deviation or imbalance charges and penalties assessed by the CAISO. 2.5 Shared Expenses. Each Co-Tenant hereby confirms its obligation to share in the payment of all costs, charges and expenses incurred in connection with the LGIA in accordance with the following provisions including, without limitation, the cost of construction of Interconnection Facilities and Network Upgrades and Interconnection Facilities Charges (and all ongoing costs associated with such facilities): (a) LGIA Costs. As between themselves (but without limiting each Co-Tenant's rights with regard to contributions from other entities under any other agreements, including the Shared Facilities Agreement), each Co-Tenant shall be responsible for the payment of its pro rata share of the LGIA Costs in proportion to such Co-Tenant's Percentage Interest. Such payment shall be paid when due to Manager, and Manager shall pay such amount to the applicable parties, unless Manager requests that each Co-Tenant pay any LGIA Costs due to CAISO or the Participating TO directly, in which case each Co-Tenant shall pay such LGIA Costs to CAISO and/or the Participating TO directly in proportion to such Co-Tenant's Percentage Interest. In either case, each Co-Tenant shall pay its share of LGIA Costs without regard to whether such Co-Tenant has issued a notice to proceed with construction of its Project prior to the date such payment is due to CAISO or the Participating TO. Notwithstanding anything to the contrary herein, any capital expenditures arising out of any equipment or facilities solely required to interconnect a particular Project shall be the sole responsibility of such Project and its Co-Tenant. (b) Collection and Payment of LGIA Costs. The Manager shall, as authorized representative for each Co-Tenant, administer the collection, payment and reimbursement of the LGIA Costs and other amounts relating to the performance of the Interconnection Customer's rights and obligations under the LGIA, including amounts due to or from the Interconnection Customer under or in connection with the LGIA. The Manager shall be responsible for invoicing the Co-Tenants their respective shares of such LGIA Costs and providing backup documentation for such invoices. The Manager shall establish procedures for invoicing and collecting payments from Co-Tenants in order to enable Manager to timely collect and pay for LGIA Costs and to enable Manager and Co-Tenants to achieve the payment requirements under and in connection with the LGIA. Each Co-Tenant shall have the right to audit, and receive periodic supporting documentation for, any expenses or other amounts required to be paid by such Co-Tenant hereunder. (c) To the extent that the Manager receives any damages, credits or refunds pursuant to the LGIA, the Manager shall promptly remit such damages, credits or refunds to the Co-Tenants according to each Co-Tenant's Percentage Interest (unless such damages, credits or refunds accrue to a specific Co-Tenant, in which event the Manager shall promptly remit them to such Co-Tenant). 2.6 Changes in Maximum Capacity. (a) The Maximum Capacity of any Project shall be increased only upon receipt by such Project's Co-Tenant of (i) written consent to such increase provided by the other Co-Tenants, such consent to be provided in each such Co-Tenant's sole discretion, (ii) all consents required under the Shared Facilities Agreement, (iii) an executed and effective new or amended LGIA that reflects the increase in Maximum Capacity and (iv) any other necessary consents by CAISO and the Participating TO. (b) The Maximum Capacity of any Project shall be decreased only upon receipt by such Project's Co-Tenant of written consent to such decrease provided by (i) CAISO and the Participating TO, and (ii) the other Co-Tenants, such consent not to be unreasonably withheld; provided however, that any such decrease in Maximum Capacity shall not decrease or change such Co-Tenant's responsibility for payment of Shared Expenses based on its initial Percentage Interest based on such Project's initial Maximum Capacity as set forth on Exhibit B hereto, including payment of LGIA Costs under Section 2.5. 2.7 Indemnity. (a) Subject to the limitations provided in Section 7.11, each Co-Tenant (an "Indemnifying Co-Tenant") shall indemnify, defend and hold harmless the other Co-Tenants (an "Indemnified Co-Tenant") and the Manager from and against any and all losses, damages, liabilities, claims, judgments, liens, penalties, costs and expenses, including, without limitation, reasonable attorneys' and consultants' fees (collectively, "Claims"), which may be (i) imposed upon or incurred by such Indemnified Co-Tenants or Manager or asserted against such Indemnified Co-Tenants or Manager as a result of any breach by the Indemnifying Co-Tenant of this Agreement or the LGIA (including, without limitation, to the extent so imposed or incurred as the result of joint liability under the LGIA), or (ii) incurred by third parties in respect of loss of, or damage to, property or injury to, or death of, persons, as a result of negligence, fraud or willful misconduct of the Indemnifying Co-Tenant or in connection with the ownership, use, operation, maintenance or repair of the Indemnifying Co-Tenant's Project. (b) Subject to the limitations provided in Sections 3.3(c) and 7.11, the Manager shall indemnify, defend, and hold harmless the Co-Tenants from any Claims which may be (i) imposed upon or incurred by such Co-Tenants as a result of gross negligence, fraud or willful misconduct of the Manager, or (ii) incurred by third parties in respect of loss of, or damage to, property or injury to, or death of, persons, as a result of negligence, fraud or willful misconduct of the Manager. 2.8 Taxes. Each Co-Tenant shall pay all real and personal property taxes and assessments, general or special, levied against its Project, including any taxes and assessments levied against such Co-Tenant's Undivided Interest in the LGIA, except for any taxes or assessments that are LGIA Costs or that are paid pursuant to the Shared Facilities Agreement. All such taxes and assessments shall be paid before delinquency and before any fine, interest or penalty shall become due or be imposed for their non-payment; provided however, that each Co-Tenant retains its rights under applicable law to seek a refund of such taxes and assessments after having paid them. 2.9 Operation and Management; Insurance. (a) Each Co-Tenant shall operate and maintain its Project Controlled Assets acting as a prudent operator and manager and otherwise (a) in accordance with the terms of the LGIA, (b) in accordance with Good Utility Practice, (c) in compliance with all Applicable Laws and Regulations, including but not limited to the Federal Power Act, as amended ("FPA"), all rules, regulations, and orders issued by the FERC pursuant to the FPA, and all laws and regulations relating to land use, hazardous substances and environmental protection, (d) in compliance with the CAISO Tariff, including the rules, protocols, procedures and standards attached thereto, as the same may be amended from time to time and approved by FERC, (e) in compliance with the rules, protocols, procedures and standards of NERC and WECC, and (f) without causing a material adverse effect on the LGIA. (b) Each Co-Tenant shall comply with its obligations under the LGIA, including with respect to its obligations to fund LGIA Costs arising under the LGIA. Each Co-Tenant shall be an "exempt wholesale generator" as such term is defined in the Public Utility Holding Company Act of 2005. (c) Each Co-Tenant shall cooperate with and timely respond to the Manager as a representative for the Co-Tenants under the LGIA, and shall provide the Manager such information, certifications and other matters as may be required to comply with the obligations under the LGIA. (d) Each Co-Tenant shall maintain insurance in accordance with the requirements of the LGIA. The Manager shall maintain insurance in accordance with the requirements of Exhibit C hereto. 2.10 Joint and Several Liability. Notwithstanding any other provision hereof, each Co-Tenant acknowledges and agrees that under the LGIA it is jointly and severally liable for (i) any payments due under the LGIA imposed on the Interconnection Customer and (ii) the performance of the obligations and duties imposed on the Interconnection Customer by the LGIA; provided that a Co-Tenant's joint and several liability under the LGIA shall not diminish or impair any Co-Tenant's rights to reimbursement or contribution from another Co-Tenant or any other Person hereunder or under any other agreement, including the Shared Facilities Agreement. Each Co-Tenant hereby agrees to, promptly upon written request, reimburse, indemnify and hold harmless the other Co-Tenants for any cost, expense or liability incurred by such other Co-Tenants to the extent resulting from its joint liability under the LGIA for such first Co-Tenant's failure to make a payment when due or perform any other obligation or duty of such Co-Tenant under the LGIA. 2.11 Disconnection. The Manager shall have the power and authority to disconnect a Project from the Point of Interconnection (1) as provided in Section 5.2, (2) upon abandonment and decommissioning of a Co-Tenant's Project as provided in Section 4.2, (3) if necessary, consistent with Good Utility Practice for the operation and maintenance of any portion of the Interconnection Facilities, (4) if the Manager determines, in its good faith discretion, that disconnection is necessary in the event of an Emergency Condition or to otherwise prevent damage or injury to persons or property, including to any other Project, the Interconnection Facilities or the property of the Participating TO or as otherwise needed to prevent or mitigate technical issues affecting the Projects, provided that the Manager will use commercially reasonable efforts to give the Co-Tenants as much advance notice as is reasonably possible under the circumstances, consistent with responding to the Emergency Condition or preventing damage or injury to persons or property, or (5) at the direction of the Participating TO or the CAISO pursuant to rights under the LGIA. Unless Manager has in its good faith determined that it is unable to do so because an imminent threat of injury or death to persons, damage to property or default under the LGIA exists, Manager shall provide notice to the relevant Co-Tenant prior to or concurrently with disconnecting its Project or as soon thereafter as is reasonably practical. 2.12 Effect of Force Majeure. If a Party is unable to carry out its obligations under this Agreement because of an event of Force Majeure, and if such Party promptly gives the other Parties written notice of such Force Majeure in reasonable detail, specifying (to the extent then known) the nature, extent and expected duration of such Force Majeure, the affected Party will be excused from the performance of its obligations hereunder to the extent such performance is prevented by such event of Force Majeure; provided that any Party affected by a Force Majeure shall diligently take all reasonable measures to mitigate or eliminate the effects of such event of Force Majeure; provided further that the suspension of a Party's performance hereunder due to Force Majeure shall be permitted solely for the duration of the effect of such Force Majeure and solely to the extent that the suspension of such Party's obligations does not cause a "Default" under the LGIA. ARTICLE III MANAGER 3.1 Appointment of Manager; Manager Services and Limitations. The Co-Tenants hereby appoint Rojo to serve as the Manager under the LGIA, subject to replacement as provided in Section 3.5 below, provided that, in accordance with the requirements of Appendix C, Section C.4.2(e) of the LGIA, Rojo in its role as Manager shall have no additional interest as an Interconnection Customer by virtue of its designation as Manager. The Manager is hereby authorized to act as the Co-Tenants' authorized agent and representative for all purposes under the LGIA (except as expressly stated herein), and, unless otherwise specifically agreed by the Co-Tenants or otherwise provided herein, the Manager shall have the power to exercise and shall exercise any and all of the rights of the Interconnection Customer under the LGIA and shall coordinate, administer and manage performance of the LGIA by the Co-Tenants. (a) Without limiting the generality of the foregoing, and subject to the limitations of authority of the Manager in Section 3.1(b) below, the Manager shall have the power, without further consent or approval of the Co-Tenants: (i) To send and receive requests, demands and other notices arising under or relating to the LGIA; (ii) To employ from time to time, at the expense of the Co-Tenants, persons, firms or corporations to render services generally needed to accomplish the purposes of the Co-Tenants with respect to the LGIA; provided that if the Manager retains any party who is an Affiliate of the Manager for any of these purposes, the fees charged shall be based on the lower of actual cost or fair market value; (iii) To pay and collect amounts due in connection with the LGIA, and to maintain one or more bank accounts wherein funds received by the Manager in connection with its duties hereunder shall be maintained; (iv) To expend monies necessary for the management and administration of the LGIA in accordance with Good Utility Practice, subject to the limitations contained herein; or (v) To execute, acknowledge, and deliver any and all instruments and take such other steps as are reasonably necessary to effectuate the foregoing and as are consistent therewith. (b) The Manager shall not without the prior, unanimous written consent of all of the Co-Tenants: (i) Create or cause to be created any lien on or security interest in the LGIA, terminate, amend or Transfer the LGIA or waive any material rights of the Co-Tenants thereunder, or initiate or settle any dispute under the LGIA; (ii) Amend or modify the terms of this Agreement, the LGIA or any other agreement to which the Co-Tenants are parties; (iii) Perform or omit to perform any act which would cause any person reasonably to believe that the Manager is authorized to bind such Co-Tenants, except as expressly provided herein, or which would cause any person reasonably to believe that the Manager is a partner of the Co-Tenant(s); (iv) Sell, assign, mortgage, encumber, convey or otherwise transfer all or any portion of any Undivided Interest; (v) Borrow funds on behalf of the Co-Tenants; (vi) Incur expenses, on behalf of the Co-Tenants, except in accordance with this Agreement and the LGIA; (vii) Enter into, on behalf of the Co-Tenants, any commitments, contracts or other agreements requiring expenditures in one year in excess of five thousand Dollars ($5,000) or with a duration of more than one (1) year; or (viii) Exercise its authority under this Agreement in a manner that results in undue preference or discrimination with respect to any Co-Tenant. (c) Manager will be reimbursed for (i) all LGIA Costs described in clauses (i) and (ii) of the definition thereof, other than costs and charges that have already been paid to CAISO and the Participating TO under the LGIA or are separately paid by the Co-Tenants, and (ii) all costs and expenses incurred in acting as Manager (including reasonable actual costs of the employees of Manager's Affiliates, including reasonable administrative and general fees and other overhead charges) and not otherwise reimbursed pursuant to clause (i) above. Any disputes regarding LGIA Costs or other costs and expenses shall be resolved pursuant to Section 5.4. 3.2 Communications. The Manager shall be the single point of contact between the Co-Tenants and CAISO and the Participating TO, and shall be responsible for all administrative obligations of the Interconnection Customer under the LGIA, including billing, issuing payments, providing notices and communicating with, and receiving instructions from, CAISO and the Participating TO with respect to the Projects and the LGIA. The Manager shall, promptly upon (and no later than one (1) calendar day following) receipt, provide to each Co-Tenant a copy of any notices or other material communications received by it under the LGIA. The Manager's actions and representations to CAISO and the Participating TO with respect to the LGIA shall be binding upon the Interconnection Customer and each individual Co-Tenant. Each Co-Tenant waives any right to individual notice or communication from CAISO or the Participating TO, and acknowledges that CAISO and the Participating TO will not be obligated to act on any instructions from a Co-Tenant, with respect to the LGIA. 3.3 Liability and Indemnification of Manager. (a) Each Co-Tenant shall, pro rata in accordance with its Percentage Interest, defend, indemnify and hold harmless the Manager and its employees and agents, from any claim, loss, liability or damage incurred by reason of any act performed or omitted to be performed by the Manager in its reasonable judgment, in good faith, or in reasonable reliance on advice of its attorneys or accountants, in connection with the LGIA or under this Agreement (other than for the Manager's own gross negligence, fraud or willful misconduct), including reasonable attorneys' fees incurred by the Manager in connection with the defense of any action based on any such alleged act or omission. The Co-Tenants agree that, so long as one of the Co-Tenants is the Manager, the foregoing indemnity means that each other Co-Tenant will only pay its pro rata shares (in accordance with its Percentage Interest) of such indemnified claims, losses, liabilities and damages. (b) The Manager shall not be liable, responsible or accountable in damages or otherwise to any Co-Tenant for any act performed in good faith by the Manager in the discharge of its duties hereunder as the Manager or in the exercise of its powers and authority hereunder or under the LGIA as the Manager, including damages arising out of the disconnection of, or the election not to disconnect, a Co-Tenant's Project from the Point of Interconnection, unless the acts or omissions of the Manager constitute gross negligence, fraud, willful misconduct or an intentional breach of this Agreement. (c) In no event shall the Manager's liability under this Agreement (for the avoidance of doubt, in the event a Co-Tenant is the Manager, without prejudice to any liability of such Co-Tenant hereunder other than in respect of its capacity as Manager), whether based on contract, indemnity, warranty, or tort (other than liability arising out of the gross negligence, fraud or willful misconduct of the Manager) exceed the amount covered and received as insurance proceeds by the Manager under the applicable insurance policies obtained by the Parties hereunder, and provided further that the Manager's liability shall be reduced by any insurance proceeds received by the relevant Co-Tenants. In no event, whether based on contract, indemnity, warranty, tort or otherwise, shall Manager, or its agents, representatives or contractors, be liable for special, incidental, exemplary, indirect, or consequential damages, including loss of profits or revenue, cost of capital, or cost of purchased power, except for damages to third parties based on personal injury or property damage; provided, however, this Section 3.3 shall not be construed as a limitation or restriction on the amount or applicability of any insurance policies obtained by the Parties hereunder. 3.4 Books and Records; Reporting. (a) Maintenance or Records. The Manager shall maintain books and records in sufficient detail to verify amounts due and payable hereunder for a period of not less than three (3) years after the end of the calendar month to which they relate, and all such books and records shall be available for inspection and/or copying by each Co-Tenant or its authorized representative at the cost and expense of such Co-Tenant and at reasonable times during regular business hours, upon reasonable notice to the Manager. (b) Provision of Records. The Manager shall, from time to time or at the reasonable request of any Co-Tenant (but not more often than once quarterly), provide reports to the Co-Tenants sufficient to keep the Co-Tenants reasonably apprised as to significant matters concerning the LGIA, the LGIA Costs, and any other amounts due under the LGIA or this Agreement. (c) Annual Statements. The Manager shall at the reasonable request of any Co-Tenant submit to the Co-Tenants an annual statement reconciling all amounts paid by each Co-Tenant during the preceding twelve (12) months against such Co-Tenant's share of all actual LGIA Costs and other amounts due from the Co-Tenants hereunder or from the Interconnection Customer under the LGIA during such twelve (12) month period, together with reasonable supporting documentation. If any Co-Tenant's share of such costs and expenses exceeds the amounts actually paid by such Co-Tenant, then such Co-Tenant shall promptly pay the amount of such difference to the Manager, who shall reimburse the other Co-Tenant(s), if and as applicable. If any Co-Tenant's share of such costs and expenses is less than the amounts actually paid by such Co-Tenant, then the Manager shall credit the amount of such overpayment by such Co-Tenant against future invoiced amounts from the Manager until such credit is exhausted. 3.5 Replacement of Manager. The Manager may only be removed upon the affirmative written direction of all of the other Co-Tenants (not including the Co-Tenant acting as the Manager hereunder and any Defaulting Party). Any replacement Manager must be approved by all of the Co-Tenants, except that the approval of a Co-Tenant that is a Defaulting Party is not required so long as the Event of Default is continuing and has not been cured. 3.6 No Discrimination. Except as otherwise provided in Sections 2.4 and 2.12, the Manager shall provide services and otherwise perform its obligations hereunder in a manner that treats each of the Co-Tenants alike under substantially similar conditions, except as required by Applicable Laws and Regulations or Good Utility Practice. 3.7 Performance. The Manager shall perform its obligations under this Agreement in accordance with all Applicable Laws and Regulations, including the FPA, the CAISO Tariff and all applicable NERC standards, the terms of the LGIA, and Good Utility Practice. 3.8 Access Rights. Each Co-Tenant shall, upon reasonable notice from Manager, provide the Manager, its agents, representatives and contractors, with reasonable access to its Project in order for Manager to carry out its rights and obligations hereunder. All such activities shall be undertaken by the Manager, its agents, representatives and contractors, in accordance with each Co-Tenant's safety protocols and procedures as then in effect. 3.9 Contracting. The Manager may delegate the performance of or engage contractors to perform its obligations under this Agreement; provided that no delegation or contracting of services by Manager shall (i) relieve Manager of its obligations or liabilities hereunder, (ii) relieve Manager of its responsibility for the completion of performance of any services rendered by any such delegate or contractor or (iii) create any relationship between the Co-Tenants, on the one hand, and any delegate or contractor, on the other. In addition, Manager shall cause each of its delegates and contractors to comply with the Manager's obligations under this Agreement to the extent applicable to such delegate's or contractor's work, including maintaining all necessary insurance not otherwise provided by the Manager. ARTICLE IV TERM 4.1 Term. The term of this Agreement will commence on the Effective Date and will terminate on the earliest of the unanimous written agreement by CAISO, the Participating TO and the Co-Tenants to (i) terminate this Agreement, provided, however, that termination in such event shall not cause a default under the LGIA, (ii) the consolidation of interest in the LGIA in a single Person, or (iii) termination of the LGIA with respect to all except for one of the Projects. The provisions of Sections 2.7, 2.10 and 3.3 will survive termination of this Agreement. 4.2 Surrender and Assignment of Undivided Interest. A Co-Tenant who wishes to abandon and decommission its Project may, subject to the unanimous agreement of the other Co-Tenants (each at its sole discretion), elect to convey its Undivided Interest and assign its rights hereunder to the other Co-Tenants and thereupon to cease to have any right, title or interest in the LGIA (such Co-Tenant, a "Surrendering Co-Tenant"). The Surrendering Co-Tenant must (a) deliver all instruments of transfer as may be necessary or appropriate to effect the conveyance of its Undivided Interest and assignment of its rights hereunder to, and which are reasonably satisfactory to, the remaining Co-Tenants, (b) assign and convey to the remaining Co-Tenants all its rights under this Agreement, free and clear of any liens, security interests or other encumbrances, provided, however, that any such surrender of an encumbered Undivided Interest may only be surrendered with the written consent of each Financing Party that holds a security interest in such Undivided Interest and a release of such Financing Party's security interest, (c) obtain all necessary consents and approvals under all Applicable Laws and Regulations prior to any such assignment, at the Surrendering Co-Tenant's sole cost and expense, (d) obtain all necessary consents and approvals under the LGIA prior to any such assignment, at the Surrendering Co-Tenant's sole cost and expense; and (e) cure all Events of Default then existing on the part of the Surrendering Co-Tenant. The Surrendering Co-Tenant shall remain fully responsible for, and shall pay all costs of obtaining the consents and approvals and of surrendering its Undivided Interest as described above. No surrender of a Co-Tenant's Undivided Interest shall relieve the Surrendering Party of any of its obligations (including but not limited to payment obligations due and payable through the effective date of its surrender of its Undivided Interest) under this Agreement, its real property rights or any other agreement entered into pursuant to this Agreement, unless expressly provided for in this Agreement, or in a writing among the Parties. ARTICLE V DEFAULT AND REMEDIES 5.1 Events of Default; Default. The following shall each constitute a default by a Party (the "Defaulting Party") under this Agreement (each an "Event of Default"): (a) a Party fails to make any payment when due under this Agreement and such Party fails to cure such default within ten (10) days ("Payment Default Cure Period") after receipt of written notice of such default; (b) a Party fails to perform any other covenant or obligation under this Agreement in any material respect, and such Party fails to cure such failure within thirty (30) days ("General Default Cure Period") after receipt of written notice of such default, provided if the nature of the defaulted obligation is such that more than thirty (30) days are reasonably required to cure such default, then the General Default Cure Period for such Event of Default shall be extended by such additional time, not to exceed ninety (90) days in total after receipt of the written notice of default, as is reasonably necessary to cure such default, provided such Party commences to cure such default promptly, and in all events within thirty (30) days after receiving notice of such default, and thereafter diligently pursues such cure to completion; (c) a Default (as defined in the LGIA) occurs as a result of the actions or inactions of such Party (for the avoidance of doubt, after giving effect to any cure periods provided in the LGIA in respect of the underlying Breach (as defined in the LGIA)); or (d) a Bankruptcy Event occurs with respect to such Party. 5.2 Remedies. (a) Following and during the continuation of an Event of Default by a Co-Tenant, each other Co-Tenant shall have the following remedies, exercisable in its sole discretion, but only after the expiration of the Payment Default Cure Period or General Default Cure Period, as applicable, if the Event of Default occurs under Sections 5.1(a) or (b): (i) To cure the default of the defaulting Co-Tenant by making or tendering the required payment or performance, and permitting the defaulting Co-Tenant's Project to continue to exercise its rights under the LGIA, provided that any such amounts paid by the non-defaulting Co-Tenant shall be treated as a loan to the defaulting Co-Tenant, which loan shall accrue interest until repaid in full at the Interest Rate; (ii) To bring an action for money damages or other appropriate relief; (iii) To bring an action to specifically enforce the provisions of this Agreement; (iv) To demand disconnection of the defaulting Co-Tenant's Project in accordance with Section 2.11 hereof, provided, that (A) the Manager shall have in good faith determined that bringing an action for money damages and/or for specific performance will not provide an adequate or timely remedy for such default, (B) the defaulting Co-Tenant's Project shall be permitted to reconnect promptly when and if the default is cured, and (C) in the case of any such reconnection, the non-defaulting Co-Tenants and the Manager shall have been compensated in full for any and all costs and damage they incurred, respectively (or, in the event the non-defaulting Co-Tenant is the Manager, that it incurred in its capacities as Co-Tenant and as Manager), as a result of such Event of Default; and/or (v) To suspend the rights of the defaulting Co-Tenant under this Agreement (including, without limitation, any rights of the defaulting Co-Tenant under this Agreement (x) to vote its respective Percentage Interest or to have such Percentage Interest counted for purposes of determining the Required Co-Tenants (whether or not so indicated), and (y) to receive any reimbursement or compensation under this Agreement, including, without limitation, pursuant to Section 2.7, except to the extent required pursuant to applicable law), including if applicable its rights as Manager, until the Event of Default has been cured; provided that no such suspension shall be deemed to suspend or otherwise affect the obligations of the defaulting Co-Tenant (including, without limitation and as applicable, in its capacity as Manager) under this Agreement. For the avoidance of doubt, during any such suspension, the defaulting Co-Tenant shall have no, and shall not be entitled to enforce any, rights under this Agreement (including, without limitation and as applicable, in its capacity as Manager); and/or (vi) To exercise any and all other rights and remedies which the non-defaulting Co-Tenant might otherwise have at law or in equity. (b) Following and during the continuation of an Event of Default by the Manager, the Required Co-Tenants (not including any Defaulting Party) shall have the following remedies, exercisable in their sole discretion, but only after the expiration of the Payment Default Cure Period or General Default Cure Period, as applicable, if the Event of Default occurs under Sections 5.1(a) or (b): (i) To remove the Manager, as provided by Section 3.5 (without limiting the provisions thereof); (ii) To cure the default of the Manager, provided any amounts paid shall be recoverable from the Manager, subject to the limitations of liability set forth in Section 3.3(c); (iii) To bring an action for money damages or other appropriate relief; (iv) To bring an action to specifically enforce the provisions of this Agreement; and/or (v) To exercise any and all other rights and remedies which they might otherwise have at law or in equity. 5.3 Equitable Relief. The Parties agree that damages may be an inadequate remedy for certain Events of Default, and that each Party shall be entitled to seek injunctive and other equitable relief, including specific performance, against any other Party or the Manager to prevent or eliminate such Event of Default. 5.4 Dispute Resolution. (a) Any controversy, claim or dispute between or among the Co-Tenants (including with the Co-Tenant acting as the Manager hereunder in its capacity as the Manager) arising out of or related to this Agreement or the breach thereof, or regarding the application or interpretation of any provision of this Agreement, that cannot be settled amicably by the Co-Tenants will be submitted first to mediation, and if mediation fails to achieve a resolution within a time period reasonably acceptable to the Co-Tenant alleging the dispute, then for binding arbitration by a three-member arbitration panel in accordance with the provisions contained herein and the Commercial Arbitration Rules of the American Arbitration Association (the "Arbitration Rules"). In arbitration, the Co-Tenants will be permitted to conduct reasonable discovery in accordance with the Federal Rules of Civil Procedure, and the Arbitration Rules will be deemed to include Fed. R. Civ. P. 26(b), 30, 31, 33, 34, and 36. The Co-Tenants will share equally in the fees and expenses of the arbitration panel. Judgment upon the award rendered by the arbitration panel may be entered in any court having jurisdiction. The arbitration panel will determine all questions of fact and law relating to any controversy, claim, or dispute hereunder, including whether or not any such controversy, claim, or dispute hereunder is subject to the arbitration provisions contained herein. (b) Any Co-Tenant desiring arbitration under this Section 5.4 (the "Demanding Party") will serve on the other Co-Tenant(s), and the Office of the American Arbitration Association in San Francisco, California, in accordance with the Rules, its demand for arbitration (the "Demand"), accompanied by the name of the person chosen by the Demanding Party to select an arbitrator with experience in the subject matter of the relevant Dispute. The responding Co-Tenant(s) will choose a second person to select an arbitrator with experience in the subject matter of the relevant Dispute, and the two persons so chosen will select the arbitration panel. All of the arbitrators will be independent and neutral. If the two persons chosen by the Parties cannot agree upon a three-member arbitration panel within thirty (30) days after the designation of the second person, then each such person may select one independent and neutral arbitrator, and the two arbitrators so selected will select a third independent and neutral arbitrator, who will serve as the panel chair. If the responding Co-Tenant(s) upon whom the Demand is served fails to advise the Demanding Party of its choice of a person to select the arbitration panel within fifteen (15) days after receipt of the Demand, or if the foregoing arbitration selection procedure fails for any other reason, the arbitrators will be selected in accordance with the Arbitration Rules. The arbitration proceedings provided hereunder are hereby declared to be self-executing, and it will not be necessary to petition a court to compel arbitration. All arbitration proceedings will be held in San Francisco, California. (c) Notice of the Demand will be filed in writing with the other Co-Tenants and with the American Arbitration Association. The Demand will be made within a reasonable time after the claim, dispute or other matter in question has arisen, and in no event will it be made after the date when institution or legal or equitable proceedings based on such claim, dispute or other matter in question would be barred by the applicable statutes of limitations. (d) Notwithstanding the foregoing, (i) the Co-Tenants may at any time seek injunctive relief from a court of competent jurisdiction, and (ii) nothing herein will prevent a Co-Tenant from defending or pursuing any claim in a court or other proceeding against a third party that has been initiated by such third party. In the event any dispute involves common issues of fact, liability or responsibility with any dispute or controversy under any other agreement (including power purchase agreements, interconnection agreements and other project agreements), each of the Co-Tenants agrees, where reasonably justified, to join such disputes and controversies to seek a common resolution of all such matters. 5.5 Notice of Default. Each Co-Tenant and the Manager shall promptly (and in any event within two (2) Business Days) provide written notice to the other Parties upon receiving notice of, or otherwise discovering, any default or potential default under this Agreement or the LGIA or receiving any other notice under the LGIA. ARTICLE VI TRANSFERABILITY 6.1 General Restriction and Obligation. No Party may Transfer all or any part of its rights and obligations under this Agreement to any another Person without the written consent of the other Parties (such consent not to be unreasonably withheld, delayed or conditioned); provided that (i) a Co-Tenant may, without the written consent of the other Parties, transfer all, but not less than all, of its Undivided Interest and other rights under this Agreement to (A) a Person to whom it is transferring all, but not less than all, of its interest in its Project and Project Controlled Assets, so long as such Person has demonstrated to the other Co-Tenant's reasonable satisfaction that it has, either directly, through an Affiliate or by contract, sufficient financial capacity and technical ability to perform its obligations under this Agreement, or (B) an Affiliate of the assigning Co-Tenant that succeeds to such assigning Co-Tenant's interests in its Project and Project Controlled Assets, but in each case only if the transferee assumes in writing all of the transferring Co-Tenant's duties, obligations and liabilities hereunder and with respect to the LGIA, and (ii) a Co-Tenant may encumber its Undivided Interest for financing purposes as provided below without the consent of the other Co-Tenants. No Transfer may occur unless all necessary consents and approvals under all Applicable Laws and Regulations and the LGIA have been obtained prior to such Transfer. In the event a Party wishes to Transfer its Undivided Interest pursuant to clauses (i) or (ii) above, it shall give the other Parties written notice of such intent, including copies of all instruments of Transfer, assumption agreements, consents and approvals, not less than thirty (30) days before effecting any such Transfer. Without prejudice to Section 6.2(a) below, all Transfers in violation of the foregoing are void. 6.2 Co-Tenant's Right to Encumber. (a) Pledge, Collateral Assignment or Encumbrance. Each Party specifically agrees that, without obtaining the consent of the other Parties, (i) any Co-Tenant may at any time pledge, collaterally assign, encumber, grant a security interest in, or, in the case of a lease financing, assign, its Undivided Interest in its rights under this Agreement and the LGIA to any Financing Party concurrently with pledging, collaterally assigning, encumbering or granting a security interest in such Co-Tenant's Project to such Financing Party, provided such Co-Tenant has first obtained all necessary consents and approvals under all Applicable Laws and Regulations and the LGIA, if any; and (ii) any Financing Party may exercise its rights under its agreement with such Co-Tenant, including foreclosing, receiving, transferring, conveying or assigning such pledged Undivided Interest; provided that such Financing Party first complies with all requirements under the LGIA and all Applicable Laws and Regulations and promptly cures all Events of Default by such Co-Tenant under Sections 5.1(a) and (b) which are capable of being cured without possession of the applicable Project after exercising such rights. Notwithstanding the foregoing, any pledge, collateral assignment or encumbrance of, or grant of a security interest in, any Co-Tenant's interest in this Agreement must include a similar pledge, collateral assignment or encumbrance of, or grant of a security interest in such Co-Tenant's interest in the LGIA. (b) Financing Parties. Should a Co-Tenant pledge, collaterally assign, encumber, grant a security interest in or assign its Undivided Interest and its rights in the LGIA as provided in Section 6.2(a) above, the Parties expressly agree among themselves and for the benefit of any Financing Party that (i) to the extent an amendment of this Agreement requires the assigning Co-Tenant's consent, no such amendment shall be implemented unless the consent of such Co-Tenant's Financing Parties of which the other Parties have received written notice is first obtained, (ii) upon the occurrence of an Event of Default by the assigning Co-Tenant, the non-defaulting Co-Tenants declaring the Event of Default shall also provide written notice of such Event of Default to the representative or agent of the Financing Parties in respect of which the assigning Co-Tenant has given the non-defaulting Co-Tenants written notice as provided below and accept such Financing Parties' cure (if any) of such Event of Default, (iii) each Financing Party shall have the same period after receipt of a notice of Event of Default to cure, or cause to be cured, the Event of Default described therein, as is given to the defaulting Co-Tenant hereunder, except that (A) the Payment Default Cure Period shall be thirty (30) days, and (B) the General Default Cure Period shall be sixty (60) days and may be extended to up to one hundred twenty (120) days in the aggregate under the conditions specified in Section 5.1(b), and (iv) if this Agreement or a Co-Tenant's interest in this Agreement is terminated or rejected as a result of a Bankruptcy Event of such Co-Tenant, the other Parties shall, upon written request of such defaulting Co-Tenant's Financing Party made within forty-five (45) days after the termination or rejection of this Agreement or the relevant Co-Tenant's interest therein, enter into a new Co-Tenancy Agreement with such Financing Party, on the same terms and conditions as this Agreement, or to the extent only the relevant Co-Tenant's interest is terminated or rejected, permit such Financing Party to join in this Agreement as a new Co-Tenant in place of the relevant Co-Tenant. Upon the execution of any such new Co-Tenancy Agreement, unless otherwise prohibited by a bankruptcy court order or by law, the Financing Party shall pay any amounts owed by the relevant Co-Tenant to the Manager or the other Co-Tenants under this Agreement and cure any Events of Default by the relevant Co-Tenant under this Agreement to the extent they can be cured. A Financing Party shall only be liable under this Agreement while it is in possession of or is the owner of an Undivided Interest and only to the extent of its interest in the relevant Co-Tenant's Project, Project Controlled Assets, Undivided Interest and interests under this Agreement and the LGIA. The non-defaulting Co-Tenants shall not be required to provide notice as provided in clause (ii) above unless the assigning Co-Tenant has, prior to the occurrence of the relevant underlying default, provided the non-defaulting Co-Tenants written notice providing such Co-Tenants with the name of a contact person, address, telephone, facsimile number and email address for a single representative or agent of the Financing Parties of such assigning Co-Tenant designated to receive such notices. (c) Estoppels and Consents. In connection with the financing of each Project, each Party will, upon the reasonable request of the Project owner and at such Project owner's cost and expense, provide customary estoppels and consents in favor of the applicable Financing Parties; provided that no Party shall be under any obligation to make any modifications to this Agreement or to incur any additional obligations under any such consent or estoppel. Each Party shall also reasonably cooperate in the making of any filings required by a Co-Tenant for compliance with Applicable Laws and Regulations and the LGIA, provided that the requesting Co-Tenant shall pay all costs reasonably incurred by the other Co-Tenants (including, without limitation, the reasonable and documented costs and expenses of counsel to such Co-Tenant) in making such filings. 6.3 FERC Approval. Notwithstanding anything in Section 6.1 or 6.2 to the contrary, no Transfer of a Co-Tenant's Undivided Interest or any of its interests in this Agreement shall be effective unless and until the Transferring Co-Tenant or the Manager has obtained any necessary prior approvals from FERC to effectuate any changes to this Agreement to reflect such Transfer and the change in the Parties to this Agreement. Any notice, demand, or communication required or permitted to be given by any provision of this Agreement shall be deemed to have been sufficiently given or served for all purposes if delivered personally or by telecopy to the Party or to an executive officer of the Party to whom the same is directed or, if sent by registered or certified mail, postage and charges prepaid, addressed to the Party's address, as appropriate, which is set forth below or to such other address as a Party shall advise the other Parties from time to time in writing. Titles of articles and sections in this Agreement are for convenience only and neither limit nor amplify the provisions of this Agreement. The unenforceability, invalidity, or illegality of any provision of this Agreement shall not affect or impair the continuing enforceability or validity of any other part, all of which shall survive and be valid and enforceable. 7.5 Waiver. No other Person may rely on any of the provisions herein contained or lay claim to any of the rights of the Parties hereto. 7.7 Counterparts; Facsimile Signatures. This Agreement may be executed in counterparts each of which when so executed and delivered shall be deemed to be an original and all of which together shall constitute one instrument. Signatures delivered by facsimile, email or other electronic means shall be binding upon the Parties hereto with the same force and effect as original signatures. 7.8 Amendments. Except as specifically provided in this Agreement, this Agreement shall not be amended except by the written agreement of all of the Parties; provided, however, that (i) Manager's consent is not required for any amendment hereof so long as its rights and obligations are not adversely affected thereby, and (ii) the consents of any Surrendering Co-Tenants shall not be required. Any amendment to this Agreement shall also be subject to consent rights that CAISO and the Participating TO may have, if any, under other agreements with the Parties. In addition, no Party may seek to amend the LGIA except with the written consent of all of the Co-Tenants. 7.9 Acknowledgement and Further Assurances. Each Party acknowledges and represents to the other Parties that this Agreement is consistent with all of the requirements set forth in the LGIA. Upon the reasonable request of any Party at any time after the Effective Date, the other Parties shall forthwith execute and deliver such further instruments of assignment, transfer, conveyance, endorsement, direction or authorization and other documents as the requesting Party may reasonably request in order to effectuate the purposes of this Agreement. Each Party agrees to reasonably cooperate with the other Parties in assisting it to comply with the terms of this Agreement, including, but not limited to, reasonable assistance in obtaining consents, waivers, authorizations, orders and/or approvals of third parties. 7.10 Waiver of Partition. The Co-Tenants each acknowledge and agree that it would be prejudicial to their interests under this Agreement if any Co-Tenant were to seek partition or any other type of division of the Interconnection Facilities or the LGIA, or file an action for such partition or division. In no event shall any Party be liable under any provision of this Agreement for any losses, damages, costs, or expenses for any special, indirect, incidental, consequential, or punitive damages, including but not limited to loss of profit or revenue, loss of the use of equipment, cost of capital, cost of temporary equipment, or services, whether based in whole or in part in contract, in tort, including negligence, strict liability, or any other theory of liability. 7.12 Co-Tenant Representative. On or promptly after the Effective Date, each Co-Tenant shall by written notice to the other Co-Tenants designate an individual representative (the "Co-Tenant Representative") whose instructions, requests, and decisions will be binding upon such Co-Tenant in all matters concerning this Agreement, except that the Co-Tenant's Representative shall not have the authority to amend this Agreement. Each Co-Tenant shall have the right to change such Co-Tenant's Representative at any time and from time to time by written notice to the other Co-Tenants and Manager. 7.13 Manager Representative. Great Valley Solar 1, LLC Market-Based Rate Tariff
1. Availability: Great Valley Solar 1, LLC (Seller) makes electric energy, capacity and ancillary services available under this Tariff for wholesale sales to purchasers with whom Seller has contracted. Seller makes certain ancillary services available under this Tariff for wholesale sales to purchasers with whom Seller has contracted, subject to the limitations below. Specifically, Seller may sell the ancillary services specified below into the following markets:
California: Seller offers regulation service, spinning reserve service, and non-spinning reserve service to the California Independent System Operator Corporation (CAISO) and to others that are self-supplying ancillary services to the CAISO. Third Party Provider: Seller offers Regulation Service, Reactive Supply and Voltage Control Service, Energy and Generator Imbalance Service, Operating Reserve-Spinning, Operating Reserve-Supplemental, and Primary Frequency Response Service. Sales will not include the following: (1) sales to an RTO or an ISO, i.e., where that entity has no ability to self-supply ancillary services but instead depends on third parties; and (2) sales to a traditional, franchised public utility affiliated with the third-party supplier, or sales where the underlying transmission service is on the system of the public utility affiliated with the third-party supplier. Sales of Operating Reserve-Spinning and Operating Reserve-Supplemental will not include sales to a public utility that is purchasing ancillary services to satisfy its own open access transmission tariff requirements to offer ancillary services to its own customers, except where the Commission has granted authorization. Sales of Regulation Service and Reactive Supply and Voltage Control Service will not include sales to a public utility that is purchasing ancillary services to satisfy its own open access transmission tariff requirements to offer ancillary services to its own customers, except at rates not to exceed the buying public utility transmission providers OATT rate for the same service or where the Commission has granted authorization.
